d|date=2013|isbn=978-0-19-936851-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last=Jensen | first=Erik | title=Barbarians in the Greek and Roman World | year=2018 | location=Cambridge; Indianapolis | publisher=Hackett Publishing | isbn=978-1-62466-712-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last=Jones | first=A.H.M. | chapter=The Fall of the Western Empire and the Barbarian Kingdoms | title=The Later Roman Empire, 284\u2013602: A Social, Economic, and Administrative Survey | volume=Vol. I | year=1964 | publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press | location=Baltimore, MD | isbn=0801832845 | ref=harv | chapter-url-access=registration | chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/laterromanempire01jone | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/laterromanempire01jone }}\n* {{cite book | last=Jordanes | year=1915 | title=The Gothic History of Jordanes | others=Translated by Charles C. Mierow | location=London | publisher=Oxford University Press | oclc=463056290 | ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last=Kim | first=Hyun Jin |year=2013|title=The Huns, Rome and the Birth of Europe |location=Cambridge; New York|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-10700-906-6| ref=harv}}\t\n* {{cite book | last=Lee | first=A.D. | year=2013 | title=From Rome to Byzantium AD 363 to 565: The Transformation of Ancient Rome | location=Edinburgh | publisher= Edinburgh University Press | isbn=978-0-74862-790-5 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Macbain |first=Bruce |year=1983 |title=Odovacer the Hun? |journal=Classical Philology |volume=78 |issue=1 |pages=323\u2013327 |jstor=269961 |ref=harv|doi=10.1086/366807 }}\n* {{cite book | last=Martindale | first=J.R. | year=1980 | chapter=Odoacer | title=The Prosopography of the Later Roman Empire | volume=Vol. 2 (A.D. 395\u2013527) | location=London; New York | publisher=Cambridge University Press | isbn=0-521-20159-4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=MacGeorge|first=Penny |title=Late Roman Warlords|year=2002|location=Oxford and New York|publisher=Oxford University P