rd, UK | publisher=Blackwell Publishing | isbn=978-0-63123-513-2 | ref=harv | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/historyofbyzanti00greg }} \n* {{cite book| last=Heather | first=Peter | year=2005 | title=The Fall of the Roman Empire: A New History of Rome and the Barbarians | place=Oxford and New York | publisher=Oxford University Press | isbn=978-0-19515-954-7 | ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Cite AmCyc|wstitle=Odoacer |short=x}}\n\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Romulus Augustus]]<br><small>as [[Western Roman Emperor]]</small><br />[[Julius Nepos]]<br><small>as [[Western Roman Emperor]]</small>}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[King of Italy]]|years=476\u2013493}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Theodoric the Great]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Barbarian kingdoms}}\n{{Germanic peoples}}\n{{Antique Kings of Italy}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:433 births]]\n[[Category:493 deaths]]\n[[Category:5th-century kings of Italy]]\n[[Category:5th-century Arian Christians]]\n[[Category:5th-century monarchs in Europe]]\n[[Category:5th-century murdered monarchs]]\n[[Category:Germanic rulers]]\n[[Category:Germanic warriors]]\n[[Category:Thuringian people]]\n[[Category:Scirii]]\n[[Category:Huns]]\n[[Category:Deaths by blade weapons]]\n[[Category:Magistri militum]]\n[[Category:Patricii]]\n[[Category:Kings of former states of Italy]]\n[[Category:Founding monarchs]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in the 470s]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in the 5th century]]\n", "name_user": "Andrew Lancaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEthnicity:word and comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Odoacer"}
{"title_page": "African Prisons Project", "text_new": "{{advert|date=February 2018}}\n{{tone|date=February 2018}}\n'''African Prisons Project''' (APP) is a charity organization working in Africa - now known as [https://www.justice-defenders.org/ Justice Defenders] - with the goal of bringing dignity and hope to prison inmates by improving access to education, healthcare, justice and reintegration into the community. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/gallery/2011/oct/17/uganda-capital-punishment|title=The African Prisons Project in Uganda|date=2011-10-17|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref> It was founded in 2004 by the British activist [[Alexander McLean (activist)|Alexander McLean]], who is currently the director.\n\n== Organizational history ==\n[[Image:Donated books arriving at Kamiti Prison.JPG|thumb|220px|Donated books arriving at Kamiti Prison]]\nIn 2004, [[Alexander McLean (activist)|Alexander McLean]] was volunteering at the [[Mulago Hospital|Mulago hospital]] in [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]]. He worked with a group of prisoners from Luzira Upper Prison. McLean observed that prison inmates were chained to their beds, with no opportunity for sanitation and no proper medical care. Despite of being terminally ill, many patients were left unsupervised. \n\n[[Alexander McLean (activist)|McLean]] visited the prison during his stay. He purchased materials to renovate the prison's infirmary, and with the support of the prison authorities, supervised the prisoners while they were renovating their own infirmary. One of the questions McLean posed to the inmates was about their needs, he observed an expressed desire for education. \n\n[[Alexander McLean (activist)|McLean]] returned to the UK where he fundraised and collected books to provide health care facilities to prisons in Uganda and for the establishment of a library at Luzira Upper Prison, to bring education about the law to prison inmates.  This event marked the beginning of  APP. Today, McLean is a member of the [[Tearfund]] Inspired Individuals Programme, along with [[Philemon Ministries|Kelvin Mwikya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inspiredindividuals.org/index.cfm?i=6818&mid=4&ministryid=21620 |title=Alexander McLean (Uganda) |publisher=Inspired Individuals |date= |accessdate=2011-02-05}}</ref>\n\n== Projects ==\nAPP is a growing UK charity and registered [[NGO]] in East Africa, with permanent bases in [[Kampala]] and [[Nairobi]], the APP community consists of local full-time staff members and a small group of permanent volunteers in the UK. There are a number of projects that APP is leading on, as part of the recently launched 2017 - 2020 strategy. A key priority area of work is establishing the world's first prison-based law college and law firm, in addition to launching the Okimanyi Project in Kenya.   \n\nAs APP continues to evolve and offer basic health and education services, the organization will continue to focus on access to justice and creating robust programmatic structures which will be handed over to Ugandan Prisons Service (UPS) as a legacy project.\n  \n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://africanprisons.org|title=Home|website=African Prisons Project}}</ref>\n{{citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\n== Condemned Choirs ==\nWhile working in the condemned section of Luzira Maximum Security Proson, McLean observed that groups of condemned prisoners, male and female, had formed choirs to sing at Sunday services, but had also been singing anti-death penalty songs. McLean mentioned to the British volunteer Martyn Ryan, that he would like to record these songs.{{citation needed|date=February 2011}} \n\nMartyn Ryan and his son Ben Ryan gathered up a group of volunteers in the UK and the team headed to Uganda in December 2007. They spent several days in the prison, recording songs by three separate choirs. Upon return to the UK, the volunteers mixed and produced an album, ''Freedom Cry''. APP used the album to raise awareness of the ongoing constitutional challenge against Uganda's death penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.condemnedchoirs.co.uk/ |title=from Luzira Prison, Uganda |publisher=Condemned Choirs |date=2009-03-26 |accessdate=2011-02-05}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nAPP and McLean have won several high-profile awards.\n\n* In 2006, McLean was named the Charity Times Volunteer of the Year in the [[UK Charity Awards]]. The award was presented to McLean by [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charitytimes.com/pages/charity_times_awards/pages/2006_finalists/2006_winners/volunteer_of_the_year.htm |title=UK Charity Awards 2006 Volunteer of the Year |publisher=Charitytimes.com |date= |accessdate=2011-02-05}}</ref>\n* In June 2007, McLean was named Alumnus of the Year by the [[University of Nottingham]] and the first Alumni Laureate at an alumni awards ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reflect.irisclients.co.uk/article/3 |title=Alumni stars are rewarded : The University of Nottingham Alumni magazine |publisher=Reflect.irisclients.co.uk |accessdate=2011-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110825205913/http://reflect.irisclients.co.uk/article/3 |archivedate=2011-08-25 }}</ref>\n* In September 2007, McLean was awarded the Real World Graduate of the Year award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herecomestheboss.com/rwa/mclean.php |title=BraveNewTalent: Videos |publisher=Herecomestheboss.com |accessdate=2011-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090728001326/http://www.herecomestheboss.com/rwa/mclean.php |archivedate=2009-07-28 }}</ref> Two months later, in November 2007, McLean was not only presented with the Beacon Prize for Young Philanthropist 2007, in recognition of his work, he was also named the Beacon Prize Overall winner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beaconfellowship.org.uk/nominate_2007.asp |title=How to nominate - The Beacon Fellowship Charitable Trust |publisher=Beaconfellowship.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-02-05}}</ref> The honour came with a cheque for \u00a330,000 for APP.\n* In September 2008, APP was a finalist in the \"Best New Charity\" category of the Charitytimes UK Charity Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charitytimes.com/pages/charity_times_awards/index.htm |title=Charity Times Awards home |publisher=Charitytimes.com |date= |accessdate=2011-02-05}}</ref>\n*In 2018, APP was a recipient of the Google Impact Challenge Award (Kenya).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://impactchallenge.withgoogle.com/kenya2018|title=Google Impact Challenge Kenya|website=Google Impact Challenge Kenya|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*https://www.justice-defenders.org/\n*[http://www.africanprisons.org/ www.africanprisons.org/]\n*[http://www.basicneeds.org www.basicneeds.org]\n*{{EW charity|1121764}}\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2006/12/11/mission_to_africa_alexander_mclean_feature.shtml www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2006/12/11/mission_to_africa_alexander_mclean_feature.shtml]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110121183624/http://www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2007/04/03/alexander_mclean_assistant_commissioner_prisons_feature.shtml web.archive.org/web/20110121183624/http://www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2007/04/03/alexander_mclean_assistant_commissioner_prisons_feature.shtml]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/6444911.stm news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/6444911.stm]\n*[http://www.independent.co.uk/student/postgraduate/prison-break-the-gap-year-student-who-set-up-a-charity-for-convicts-in-africa-396512.html www.independent.co.uk/student/postgraduate/prison-break-the-gap-year-student-who-set-up-a-charity-for-convicts-in-africa-396512.html]\n*[http://www.indymedia.org.uk/en/regions/manchester/2006/07/344369.html www.indymedia.org.uk/en/regions/manchester/2006/07/344369.html]\n*[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/article1492149.ece entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/article1492149.ece]\n\n{{Incarceration}}\n\n[[Category:Development charities based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Law in Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=February 2018}}\n{{tone|date=February 2018}}\n'''African Prisons Project''' (APP) is a charity organization working in Africa - now known as [https://www.justice-defenders.org/ Justice Defenders] - with the goal of bringing dignity and hope to prison inmates by improving access to education, healthcare, justice and reintegration into the community. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/gallery/2011/oct/17/uganda-capital-punishment|title=The African Prisons Project in Uganda|date=2011-10-17|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref> It was founded in 2004 by the British activist [[Alexander McLean (activist)|Alexander McLean]], who is currently the director.\n\n== Organizational history ==\n[[Image:Donated books arriving at Kamiti Prison.JPG|thumb|220px|Donated books arriving at Kamiti Prison]]\nIn 2004, [[Alexander McLean (activist)|Alexander McLean]] was volunteering at the [[Mulago Hospital|Mulago hospital]] in [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]]. He worked with a group of prisoners from Luzira Upper Prison. McLean observed that prison inmates were chained to their beds, with no opportunity for sanitation and no proper medical care. Despite of being terminally ill, many patients were left unsupervised. \n\n[[Alexander McLean (activist)|McLean]] visited the prison during his stay. He purchased materials to renovate the prison's infirmary, and with the support of the prison authorities, supervised the prisoners while they were renovating their own infirmary. One of the questions McLean posed to the inmates was about their needs, he observed an expressed desire for education. \n\n[[Alexander McLean (activist)|McLean]] returned to the UK where he fundraised and collected books to provide health care facilities to prisons in Uganda and for the establishment of a library at Luzira Upper Prison, to bring education about the law to prison inmates.  This event marked the beginning of  APP. Today, McLean is a member of the [[Tearfund]] Inspired Individuals Programme, along with [[Philemon Ministries|Kelvin Mwikya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inspiredindividuals.org/index.cfm?i=6818&mid=4&ministryid=21620 |title=Alexander McLean (Uganda) |publisher=Inspired Individuals |date= |accessdate=2011-02-05}}</ref>\n\n== Projects ==\nAPP is a growing UK charity and registered [[NGO]] in East Africa, with permanent bases in [[Kampala]] and [[Nairobi]], the APP community consists of local full-time staff members and a small group of permanent volunteers in the UK. There are a number of projects that APP is leading on, as part of the recently launched 2017 - 2020 strategy. A key priority area of work is establishing the world\u2019s first prison-based law college and law firm, in addition to launching the Okimanyi Project in Kenya.   \n\nAs APP continues to evolve and offer basic health and education services, the organization will continue to focus on access to justice and creating robust programmatic structures which will be handed over to Ugandan Prisons Service (UPS) as a legacy project.\n  \n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://africanprisons.org|title=Home|website=African Prisons Project}}</ref>\n{{citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\n== Condemned Choirs ==\nWhile working in the condemned section of Luzira Maximum Security Proson, McLean observed that groups of condemned prisoners, male and female, had formed choirs to sing at Sunday services, but had also been singing anti-death penalty songs. McLean mentioned to the British volunteer Martyn Ryan, that he would like to record these songs.{{citation needed|date=February 2011}} \n\nMartyn Ryan and his son Ben Ryan gathered up a group of volunteers in the UK and the team headed to Uganda in December 2007. They spent several days in the prison, recording songs by three separate choirs. Upon return to the UK, the volunteers mixed and produced an album, ''Freedom Cry''. APP used the album to raise awareness of the ongoing constitutional challenge against Uganda's death penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.condemnedchoirs.co.uk/ |title=from Luzira Prison, Uganda |publisher=Condemned Choirs |date=2009-03-26 |accessdate=2011-02-05}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nAPP and McLean have won several high-profile awards.\n\n* In 2006, McLean was named the Charity Times Volunteer of the Year in the [[UK Charity Awards]]. The award was presented to McLean by [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charitytimes.com/pages/charity_times_awards/pages/2006_finalists/2006_winners/volunteer_of_the_year.htm |title=UK Charity Awards 2006 Volunteer of the Year |publisher=Charitytimes.com |date= |accessdate=2011-02-05}}</ref>\n* In June 2007, McLean was named Alumnus of the Year by the [[University of Nottingham]] and the first Alumni Laureate at an alumni awards ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reflect.irisclients.co.uk/article/3 |title=Alumni stars are rewarded : The University of Nottingham Alumni magazine |publisher=Reflect.irisclients.co.uk |accessdate=2011-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110825205913/http://reflect.irisclients.co.uk/article/3 |archivedate=2011-08-25 }}</ref>\n* In September 2007, McLean was awarded the Real World Graduate of the Year award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herecomestheboss.com/rwa/mclean.php |title=BraveNewTalent: Videos |publisher=Herecomestheboss.com |accessdate=2011-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090728001326/http://www.herecomestheboss.com/rwa/mclean.php |archivedate=2009-07-28 }}</ref> Two months later, in November 2007, McLean was not only presented with the Beacon Prize for Young Philanthropist 2007, in recognition of his work, he was also named the Beacon Prize Overall winner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beaconfellowship.org.uk/nominate_2007.asp |title=How to nominate - The Beacon Fellowship Charitable Trust |publisher=Beaconfellowship.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-02-05}}</ref> The honour came with a cheque for \u00a330,000 for APP.\n* In September 2008, APP was a finalist in the \"Best New Charity\" category of the Charitytimes UK Charity Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charitytimes.com/pages/charity_times_awards/index.htm |title=Charity Times Awards home |publisher=Charitytimes.com |date= |accessdate=2011-02-05}}</ref>\n*In 2018, APP was a recipient of the Google Impact Challenge Award (Kenya).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://impactchallenge.withgoogle.com/kenya2018|title=Google Impact Challenge Kenya|website=Google Impact Challenge Kenya|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*https://www.justice-defenders.org/\n*[http://www.africanprisons.org/ www.africanprisons.org/]\n*[http://www.basicneeds.org www.basicneeds.org]\n*{{EW charity|1121764}}\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2006/12/11/mission_to_africa_alexander_mclean_feature.shtml www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2006/12/11/mission_to_africa_alexander_mclean_feature.shtml]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110121183624/http://www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2007/04/03/alexander_mclean_assistant_commissioner_prisons_feature.shtml web.archive.org/web/20110121183624/http://www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2007/04/03/alexander_mclean_assistant_commissioner_prisons_feature.shtml]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/6444911.stm news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/6444911.stm]\n*[http://www.independent.co.uk/student/postgraduate/prison-break-the-gap-year-student-who-set-up-a-charity-for-convicts-in-africa-396512.html www.independent.co.uk/student/postgraduate/prison-break-the-gap-year-student-who-set-up-a-charity-for-convicts-in-africa-396512.html]\n*[http://www.indymedia.org.uk/en/regions/manchester/2006/07/344369.html www.indymedia.org.uk/en/regions/manchester/2006/07/344369.html]\n*[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/article1492149.ece entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/article1492149.ece]\n\n{{Incarceration}}\n\n[[Category:Development charities based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Law in Africa]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProjects:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/African_Prisons_Project"}
{"title_page": "Public Health Emergency of International Concern", "text_new": "{{short description|Formal declaration by the World Health Organization}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:World Health Organization Logo.svg|thumb|Logo of the World Health Organization, the authority which declares PHEIC]]\nA '''Public Health Emergency of International Concern''' ('''PHEIC''', pronounced \"fake\"<ref name=Van-Tam2010>{{Cite book|last=Van-Tam|first=Jonathan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_IYYr9cjE30C&pg=PA195|title=Introduction to Pandemic Influenza|last2=Sellwood|first2=Chloe|date=2010|publisher=CABI|location=Wallingford, Oxford|isbn=978-1-84593-625-9|language=en}}</ref>) is a formal declaration by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) of \"an extraordinary event which is determined to constitute a public health risk to other States through the international spread of disease and to potentially require a coordinated international response\", formulated when a situation arises that is \"serious, sudden, unusual or unexpected\", which \"carries implications for public health beyond the affected state's national border\" and \"may require immediate international action\".<ref name=WHOIHR1>WHO Q&A (19 June 2019). {{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/features/qa/emergency-committees/en/|title= International Health Regulations and Emergency Committees|website=WHO|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref> Under the 2005 [[International Health Regulations]] (IHR), states have a legal duty to respond promptly to a PHEIC.<ref name=\"urlInside Justice-WHO-PHEIC\"/> The declaration is publicized by an Emergency Committee (EC) made up of international experts operating under the IHR (2005),<ref name=\"WHO-IHR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/ihr/about/en/|title=Strengthening health security by implementing the International Health Regulations (2005); About IHR|publisher=WHO|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref> which was developed following the [[Timeline of the SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak]] of 2002\u201303.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" />\n\nSince 2009 there have been six PHEIC declarations:<ref name=\"WashPost2016\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/02/02/who-declared-a-public-health-emergency-about-zikas-effects-here-are-three-takeaways/|title=WHO declared a public health emergency about Zika's effects. Here are three takeaways|last=Pillinger|first=Mara|date=2 February 2016|access-date=19 June 2019|work=Washington Post}}{{subscription required}}</ref> the [[2009 flu pandemic|2009 H1N1 (or swine flu) pandemic]], the [[Poliomyelitis eradication#2011\u20132015|2014 polio declaration]], the [[2014 West Africa Ebola outbreak|2014 outbreak of Ebola in Western Africa]], the [[2015\u201316 Zika virus epidemic]],<ref name=\"Hunger2018\"/> the ongoing [[Kivu Ebola epidemic|2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola epidemic]],<ref name=\"WHO18Oct2019\"/> and the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], declared a PHEIC by the Director-General on 30 January 2020.<ref name=\"WHOStatement30January2020\">WHO Statement (31 January 2020). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|title=Statement on the second meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|last=|first=|date=31 January 2020|website=World Health Organisation|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref> The recommendations are temporary and require reviews every three months.<ref name=WHOIHR1/>\n\n[[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]], [[smallpox]], [[wild type]] [[poliomyelitis]], and any new subtype of [[human influenza]] are automatically PHEICs and thus do not require an IHR decision to declare them as such.<ref name=Hall2018>{{cite book|author1=Mark A. Hall|author2=David Orentlicher|author3=Mary Anne Bobinski|author4=Nicholas Bagley|author5=I. Glenn Cohen|title=Health Care Law and Ethics|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mwJODwAAQBAJ&pg=PA908|edition=9th|date=26 February 2018|publisher=Wolters Kluwer |location=New York|isbn=978-1-4548-8180-3|page=908|chapter=8. Public Health Law}}</ref> A PHEIC is not confined to infectious diseases, and may cover an emergency caused by exposure to a chemical agent or radioactive material.<ref name=Halabi2017>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nvzmDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA110 |title=Global Management of Infectious Disease After Ebola|last=Halabi|first=Sam F.|last2=Crowley|first2=Jeffrey S.|last3=Gostin|first3=Lawrence Ogalthorpe|date=2017|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=9780190604882|location=|pages=110|language=en}}</ref> In any case within its ambit, it is a \"call to action\" and \"last resort\" measure.<ref name=\"Rull2015\">{{Cite journal|last=Rull|first=Monica|last2=Kickbusch|first2=Ilona|last3=Lauer|first3=Helen|date=8 December 2015|title=Policy Debate {{!}} International Responses to Global Epidemics: Ebola and Beyond|journal=International Development Policy|language=en|volume=6|issue=2|doi=10.4000/poldev.2178|issn=1663-9375}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nMultiple surveillance and response systems exist worldwide for the early detection and effective response to contain the spread of disease. Time delays still occur for two main reasons, however. The first is the delay between the [[index case|first case]] and the confirmation of the outbreak by the healthcare system, allayed by good surveillance via data collection, evaluation, and organisation. The second is when there is a delay between the detection of the outbreak and widespread recognition and declaration of it as an international concern.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> The declaration is promulgated by an Emergency Committee (EC) made up of international experts operating under the IHR (2005),<ref name=\"WHO-IHR2\"/> which was developed following the [[Timeline of the SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak]] of 2002/2003.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> Between 2009 and 2016, there were four PHEIC declarations.<ref name=\"WashPost2016\"/> The fifth was the 2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola epidemic which was announced on 17 July 2019.<ref name=\"WHO18Oct2019\"/> The sixth is the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 novel coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"WHOStatement30January2020\"/> Under the 2005 [[International Health Regulations]] (IHR), States have a legal duty to respond promptly to a PHEIC.<ref name=\"urlInside Justice-WHO-PHEIC\"/>\n\n==Definition==\nPHEIC is defined as; <blockquote>an extraordinary event which is determined to constitute a public health risk to other States through the international spread of disease and to potentially require a coordinated international response<ref name=WHO2016>WHO Regulations (2005). {{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/ihr/annex_2/en/|title=WHO {{!}} Annex 2 of the International Health Regulations (2005)|website=WHO|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThis definition designates a [[public health crisis]] of potentially global reach and implies a situation that is \"serious, sudden, unusual or unexpected\", which may necessitate immediate international action.<ref name=WHO2016/><ref name=Exter2015>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FhMACwAAQBAJ&pg=PA540|title=International Health Law and Ethics: Basic Documents|last=Exter|first=Andr\u00e9 den|date=2015|publisher=Maklu|isbn=9789046607923|edition=3rd|series=|location=|pages=540|language=en|chapter=Part VI Public Health; Chapter 1.1 International Health Regulations (2005)}}</ref>\n\nIt is a \"call to action\" and \"last resort\" measure.<ref name=\"Rull2015\"/>\n\n==Reporting a potential concern==\nWHO Member States have 24 hours within which to report potential PHEIC events to the WHO.<ref name=Hall2018/> It does not have to be a member State that reports a potential outbreak, hence reports to the WHO can also be received informally.<ref name=Davies2015/>\nUnder the IHR (2005), ways to detect, evaluate, notify and report events were ascertained by all countries in order to avoid PHEICs. The response to public health risks was also decided.<ref name=Rull2015/>\n\nThe IHR decision algorithm assists WHO Member States in deciding whether a potential PHEIC exists and the WHO should be notified. The WHO should be notified if any two of the four following questions are affirmed:<ref name=Hall2018/>\n*Is the public health impact of the event serious?\n*Is the event unusual or unexpected?\n*Is there a significant risk for international spread?\n*Is there a significant risk for international travel or trade restrictions?\n\nThe PHEIC criteria include a list of diseases that are always notifiable.<ref name=Davies2015>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=kvvVBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA61 |title=Disease Diplomacy: International Norms and Global Health Security|last=Davies|first=Sara E.|last2=Kamradt-Scott|first2=Adam|last3=Rushton|first3=Simon|date=2015|publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University Press]]|isbn=9781421416489|language=en}}</ref> [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]], [[smallpox]], [[wild type]] [[poliomyelitis]] and any new subtype of [[human influenza]] are always a PHEIC and do not require an IHR decision to declare them as such.<ref name=WHO2016/>\n\nQuotidian epidemics which public attention do fulfill the criteria to be a PHEIC.<ref name=\"Rull2015\"/> EC's were not convened for the [[2010s Haiti cholera outbreak|cholera outbreak in Haiti]], [[Ghouta chemical attack|chemical weapons use in Syria]] or the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|Fukushima nuclear disaster in Japan]], for example.<ref name=Halabi2017/><ref name=Gostin2016/>\n\nFurther assessment is required for diseases which are prone to [[pandemic]]s, including but not limited to [[cholera]], [[pneumonic plague]], [[yellow fever]], and viral hemorrhagic fevers.<ref name=Gostin2016/>\n\nA declaration of a PHEIC may appear as an economic burden to the state facing the epidemic. Incentives to declare an epidemic are lacking and the PHEIC can be seen as placing limitations on trade in countries that are already struggling.<ref name=Rull2015/>\n\n==Emergency committee==\nIn order to declare a PHEIC, the [[WHO#Director-General|WHO Director-General]] is required to take into account factors which include the risk to human health and international spread as well as advice from an internationally made up committee of experts, the IHR Emergency Committee (EC), one of which should be an expert nominated by the State within whose region the event arises.<ref name=WHOIHR1/> Rather than being a standing committee, the EC is created [[ad hoc]].<ref name=Kamradt-Scott2019>{{Cite journal|last=Kamradt-Scott|first=Adam|last2=Eccleston-Turner|first2=Mark|date=1 April 2019|title=Transparency in IHR emergency committee decision making: the case for reform|url=https://gh.bmj.com/content/4/2/e001618|journal=British Medical Journal Global Health|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=e001618|doi=10.1136/bmjgh-2019-001618|pmid=31139463|pmc=6509695|issn=2059-7908|via=}}</ref>\n\nUntil 2011, the names of IHR EC members were not publicly disclosed. These members are selected according to the disease in question and the nature of the event. The Director-General takes the EC's advice following their technical assessment of the crisis using legal criteria and a predetermined algorithm after a review of all available data on the event. Upon declaration, the EC then makes recommendations on what actions the Director-General and Member States should take to address the crisis.<ref name=Kamradt-Scott2019/> The recommendations are temporary and require three-monthly reviews.<ref name=WHOIHR1/>\n\n==Declarations==\n[[File:H1N1 influenza virus.jpg|thumb|upright|H1N1 influenza virus]]\n\n===2009 swine flu declaration===\nIn the spring of 2009, a novel influenza A (H1N1) virus emerged. It was detected first in the United States of America and spread quickly across the United States and the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/flu/pandemic-resources/2009-h1n1-pandemic.html|title=2009 H1N1 Pandemic|last=CDC|date=2019-06-11|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> On 26 April 2009,<ref name=H1N12009WHO>{{Cite book|url=http://apps.who.int/gb/ebwha/pdf_files/WHA64/A64_10-en.pdf|title=Implementation of the International Health Regulations (2005), Report of the Review Committee on the Functioning of the International Health Regulations (2005) in relation to Pandemic (H1N1) 2009|last=Director-General|publisher=WHO|year=2009|isbn=|location=|pages=118}}</ref> more than one month after its first emergence,<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\">{{Cite journal|last=Hoffman|first=Steven J.|last2=Silverberg|first2=Sarah L.|date=18 January 2018|title=Delays in Global Disease Outbreak Responses: Lessons from H1N1, Ebola, and Zika|journal=[[American Journal of Public Health]]|volume=108|issue=3|pages=329\u2013333|doi=10.2105/AJPH.2017.304245|pmid=29345996|pmc=5803810|issn=0090-0036}}</ref> the first PHEIC was declared when the [[2009 flu pandemic|H1N1 (or swine flu) pandemic]] was still in [[Influenza pandemic#Phases|Phase Three]].<ref name=\"urlInside Justice-WHO-PHEIC\">{{cite web| url = http://www.insidejustice.com/intl/2009/04/30/swine_flu_who_pheic/| title = Inside Justice &#124; Swine Flu: Legal Obligations and Consequences When the World Health Organization Declares a \"Public Health Emergency of International Concern\"| author =  Renee Dopplick| date = 29 April 2009| accessdate = 6 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"urlWHO | Swine influenza\">{{cite web| url = http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2009/h1n1_20090425/en/\n| title = Swine influenza| author = Margaret Chan | date = 25 April 2009| publisher = [[World Health Organization]]| accessdate = 6 June 2014| author-link = Margaret Chan}}</ref><ref name=\"urlWHO | Swine flu illness in the United States and Mexico - update 2\">{{cite web| url = http://www.who.int/csr/don/2009_04_26/en/| title = Swine flu illness in the United States and Mexico \u2013 update 2| author = | date = 26 April 2009| publisher = [[World Health Organization]]| accessdate = 6 June 2014}}</ref> On the same day, within three hours the WHO web site received almost two million visits, necessitating the pandemic's own dedicated pandemic influenza web site.<ref name=H1N12009WHO/> At the time H1N1 had been declared a PHEIC, it had so far occurred in only three countries.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> Declaring H1N1 a PHEIC has therefore been argued as fueling public fear.<ref name=\"Gostin2016\">{{Cite journal|last=Gostin|first=Lawrence O.|last2=Katz|first2=Rebeccas|author-link2=Rebecca Katz|date=June 2016|title=The International Health Regulations: The Governing Framework for Global Health Security|url=|journal=The Milbank Quarterly|volume=94|issue=2|pages=264\u2013313|doi=10.1111/1468-0009.12186|pmc=4911720|pmid=27166578|via=}}</ref> However, a 2013 study sponsored by the WHO estimated that although the H1N1 pandemic was similar in magnitude to seasonal influenza, it resulted in the loss of more life-years due to a shift toward mortality among persons less than 65 years of age.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Simonsen |first=Lone |last2=Spreeuwenberg |first2=Peter |last3=Lustig |first3=Roger |last4=Taylor |first4=Robert J. |last5=Fleming |first5=Douglas M. |last6=Kroneman |first6=Madelon |last7=Van Kerkhove |first7=Maria D. |last8=Mounts |first8=Anthony W. |last9=Paget |first9=W. John |last10=Hay |first10=Simon I. |title=Global Mortality Estimates for the 2009 Influenza Pandemic from the GLaMOR Project: A Modeling Study |journal=[[PLOS Medicine]] |date=26 November 2013 |volume=10 |issue=11 |pages=e1001558 |doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001558 |pmid=24302890 |pmc=3841239}}</ref>\n\n===2014 polio declaration===\nThe second PHEIC was the [[Poliomyelitis eradication#2011\u20132015|2014 polio declaration]], issued in May 2014 with the resurgence of [[poliomyelitis|wild polio]] after its near-eradication, deemed \"an extraordinary event\".<ref name=\"urlWHO-IHREC-wild poliovirus\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2014/polio-20140505/en/\n| title = WHO &#124; WHO statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations Emergency Committee concerning the international spread of wild poliovirus\n| author = \n| date = 5 May 2014\n| publisher = [[World Health Organization]]\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref><ref name=\"urlNewScientist-polio cases surge-2014-0505\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn25518-global-emergency-declared-as-polio-cases-surge.html\n| title = Global emergency declared as polio cases surge \u2013 health \u2013 05 May 2014 \u2013 New Scientist\n| first =  Debora\n| last = MacKenzie\n| date = 5 May 2014\n| publisher = New Scientist\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nGlobal eradication was deemed to be at risk with small numbers of cases in Afghanistan, Pakistan, and Nigeria.<ref name=Gostin2016/>\n\nIn October 2019, continuing cases of wild polio in Pakistan and Afghanistan, in addition to new vaccine-derived cases in Africa and Asia, was reviewed and remains a PHEIC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/10/news-scan-oct-04-2019|title=News Scan: Polio in Pakistan|last=|first=|date=4 October 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> It was extended on 11 December 2019.<ref name=THP11Dec2019>{{Cite web|url=https://travelhealthpro.org.uk/news/483/polio-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern|title=NaTHNaC - Polio: Public Health Emergency of International Concern|last=|first=|date=|website=TravelHealthPro|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2014 Ebola declaration===\nConfirmed cases of Ebola were being reported in Guinea and Liberia in March 2014 and Sierra Leone by May 2014. On Friday, 8 August 2014, following the occurrence of Ebola in the United States and Europe and with the already intense transmission ongoing in three other countries for months,<ref name=Rull2015/> the WHO declared its third PHEIC in response to the [[2014 West Africa Ebola outbreak|outbreak of Ebola in Western Africa]].<ref name=WHO2014>{{Cite web|url=http://www.euro.who.int/en/health-topics/emergencies/pages/news/news/2014/08/ebola-outbreak-in-west-africa-declared-a-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern|title=Ebola outbreak in West Africa declared a public health emergency of international concern|date=8 August 2014|website=www.euro.who.int|language=en|access-date=3 June 2019}}</ref> Later, one review showed that a direct impact of this epidemic on America escalated a PHEIC declaration.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> It was the first PHEIC in a resource-poor setting.<ref name=Rull2015/>\n\n===2016 Zika virus declaration===\nOn 1 February 2016, the WHO declared its fourth PHEIC in response to clusters of [[microcephaly]] and [[Guillain\u2013Barr\u00e9 syndrome]] in the [[Americas]], which at the time were suspected to be associated with the ongoing [[2015\u201316 Zika virus epidemic]].<ref>WHO (1 February 2016). [http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2016/emergency-committee-zika-microcephaly/en/ WHO Director-General summarizes the outcome of the Emergency Committee on Zika]</ref> Later research and evidence bore out these concerns; in April, the WHO stated that \"there is scientific consensus that Zika virus is a cause of microcephaly and Guillain\u2013Barr\u00e9 syndrome.\"<ref name=\"WHO SitRep 7 Apr 2016\">{{cite web | url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/204961/1/zikasitrep_7Apr2016_eng.pdf?ua=1 | title=Zika Virus Microcephaly And Guillain\u2013Barr\u00e9 Syndrome Situation Report | publisher=World Health Organization | date=7 April 2016 | accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref>  This was the first time a PHEIC was declared for a [[Mosquito-borne disease|mosquito\u2010borne disease]].<ref name=Gostin2016/> This declaration was lifted on 18 November 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fifth meeting of the Emergency Committee under the International Health Regulations (2005) regarding microcephaly, other neurological disorders and Zika virus|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2016/zika-fifth-ec/en/|website=World Health Organization|publisher=WHO|accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola declaration ===\nIn October 2018 and then later in April 2019, the WHO did not consider the [[2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola epidemic]] to be a PHEIC.<ref name=\"Green20April2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Green|first=Andrew|date=20 April 2019|title=DR Congo Ebola outbreak not given PHEIC designation|journal=The Lancet|volume=393|issue=10181|pages=1586|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(19)30893-1|pmid=31007190}}</ref><ref name=\"PHEICApril2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/12-04-2019-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-for-ebola-virus-disease-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo-on-12th-april-2019|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee for Ebola virus disease in the Democratic Republic of the Congo on 12th April 2019|date=12 April 2019|publisher=World Health Organization|accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref> The decision was controversial, with [[Michael Osterholm]], director of the [[Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy]] (CIDRAP) responding with disappointment and describing the situation as \"an Ebola gas can sitting in DRC that's just waiting for a match to hit it\",<ref name=\"Cohen2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2019/04/ebola-outbreak-congo-still-not-international-crisis-who-decides|title=Ebola outbreak in Congo still not an international crisis, WHO decides|last=Cohen|first=Jon|last2=2019|date=12 April 2019|website=Science {{!}} AAAS|language=en|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> while the WHO panel were unanimous that declaring it a PHEIC would not give any added benefit.<ref name=\"Cohen2019\" /> The advice against declaring a PHEIC in October 2018 and April 2019, despite the criteria for doing so appearing to be met on both occasions has led to the transparency of the IHR EC coming into question. The language used in the statements for the Kivu Ebola epidemic has been noted to be different. In October 2018, the EC stated \"a PHEIC should not be declared at this time\". However, in the 13 previously declined proposals for declaring a PHEIC, the resultant statements quoted \"the conditions for a PHEIC are not currently met\" and \"does not constitute a PHEIC\". In April 2019, they stated that \"there is no added benefit to declaring a PHEIC at this stage\", a notion that is not part of the PHEIC criteria laid down in the IHR.<ref name=\"Kamradt-Scott2019\" /><ref name=\"Lancet2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Lancet|first=The|date=25 May 2019|title=Acknowledging the limits of public health solutions|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(19)31183-3/abstract|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=393|issue=10186|pages=2100|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(19)31183-3|issn=0140-6736|pmid=31226033}}</ref>\n\nAfter confirmed cases of Ebola in neighbouring Uganda in June 2019, [[Tedros Adhanom]], the Director-General of the WHO, announced that the third meeting of a group of experts would be held on 14 June 2019 to assess whether the Ebola spread had become a PHEIC.<ref name=\"Hunt2019\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/06/12/health/ebola-outbreak-death-uganda-africa-intl-bn/index.html|title=Ebola outbreak enters 'truly frightening phase' as it turns deadly in Uganda|last=Hunt|first=Katie|website=CNN|language=en|accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes14June2019\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/world/africa/ebola-uganda-congo.html|title=Boy, 5, and Grandmother Die in Uganda as More Ebola Cases Emerge|last=Gladstone|first=Rick|date=12 June 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=14 June 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The conclusion was that while the outbreak was a health emergency in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] (DRC) and the region, it does not meet all the three criteria for a PHEIC.<ref name=\"WHO14June2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/14-06-2019-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-for-ebola-virus-disease-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee for Ebola virus disease in the Democratic Republic of the Congo on 14 June 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=World Health Organization|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 June 2019}}</ref> Despite the number of deaths reaching 1,405 by 11 June 2019 and 1,440 by 17 June 2019, the reason for not declaring a PHIEC was that the overall risk of international spread was deemed to be low, and the risk of damaging the economy of the DRC high.<ref name=\"SoucharyJune2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/06/ebola-case-counts-spike-again-drc|title=Ebola case counts spike again in DRC|last=Souchary|first=Stephanie|date=17 June 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=24 June 2019}}</ref> Adhanom also stated that declaring a PHEIC would be an inappropriate way to raise money for the epidemic.<ref name=\"CIDRAP16July2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/07/who-will-take-ebola-emergency-declaration-question-fourth-time|title=WHO will take up Ebola emergency declaration question for a fourth time|last=Soucheray|first=Stephanie|last2=2019|date=16 July 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=17 July 2019}}</ref> Following a visit to the DRC in July 2019, [[Rory Stewart]], the UK's [[Department for International Development|DfID]] minister, called for the WHO to declare it an emergency.<ref name=\"Wintour9July2019\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/07/declare-ebola-outbreak-in-drc-an-emergency-says-uks-rory-stewart|title=Declare Ebola outbreak in DRC an emergency, says UK's Rory Stewart|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=7 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=9 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nAcknowledging a high risk of spread to the capital of North Kivu, [[Goma]], a call for a PHEIC declaration was published on 10 July 2019 in the ''[[Washington Post]]'' by [[Daniel R. Lucey|Daniel Lucey]] and [[Ron Klain]] (the former US [[Ebola response coordinator]]). They stated that  \"in the absence of a trajectory toward extinguishing the outbreak, the opposite path\u2014severe escalation\u2014remains possible. The risk of the disease moving into nearby Goma, Congo\u2014a city of 1 million residents with an international airport \u2014or crossing into the massive refugee camps in South Sudan is mounting. With a limited number of vaccine doses remaining, either would be a catastrophe\".<ref name=\"Soucheray11July2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/07/three-more-health-workers-infected-ebola-outbreak|title=Three more health workers infected in Ebola outbreak|last=Soucheray|first=Stephanie|date=11 July 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Klain10July2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/its-time-to-declare-a-public-health-emergency-on-ebola/2019/07/10/c77641fc-a327-11e9-b732-41a79c2551bf_story.html|title=Opinion {{!}} It's time to declare a public health emergency on Ebola|last=Klain|first=Ronald A.|last2=Lucey|first2=Daniel|date=10 July 2019|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref> Four days later, on 14 July 2019, a case of Ebola was confirmed in Goma, which has an international airport and a highly mobile population. Subsequently, the WHO announced a reconvening of a fourth EC meeting on 17 July 2019, when they officially announced it \"a regional emergency, and by no means a global threat\" and declared it as a PHEIC, without restrictions on trade or travel.<ref name=\"WHONewsRelease17July2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/17-07-2019-ebola-outbreak-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo-declared-a-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern|title=Ebola outbreak in the Democratic Republic of the Congo declared a Public Health Emergency of International Concern|last=|first=|date=2019-07-17|website=World Health Organization|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref><ref name=BBCNews17July2019>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-49025298|title=Ebola outbreak declared public health emergency|last=|first=|date=17 July 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=17 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> In response to the declaration, the president of the DRC, together with an expert committee led by a virologist, took responsibility for directly supervising action, while in protest of the declaration, health minister, [[Oly Ilunga Kalenga]] resigned.<ref name=Schnirring22July2019>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/07/drc-health-minister-resigns-after-government-takes-ebola-reins|title=DRC health minister resigns after government takes Ebola reins|last=Schnirring|first=Lisa|date=22 July 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> A review of the PHEIC had been planned at a fifth meeting of the EC on 10 October 2019<ref name=9Oct2019>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/10/response-resumes-following-security-problems-drc-ebola-hot-spot|title=Response resumes following security problems in DRC Ebola hot spot|last=Schnirring|first=Lisa|last2=9 October 2019|date=|website=CIDRAP|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> and as of 18 October 2019, it continues to be a PHEIC.<ref name=\"WHO18Oct2019\">WHO Statement (18 October 2019). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/18-10-2019-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-for-ebola-virus-disease-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee for Ebola virus disease in the Democratic Republic of the Congo on 18 October 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=www.who.int|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 coronavirus pandemic (COVID-19) ===\n[[File:2019-nCoV-CDC-23312.png|thumb|right|Morphology of SARS-CoV-2]]\nOn 30 January 2020, the WHO declared the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|outbreak of COVID-19]], centered on [[Wuhan]] in [[central China]], a PHEIC.<ref name=\"WHOStatement30January2020\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/30/health/coronavirus-world-health-organization.html |title=W.H.O. Declares Global Emergency as the new Coronavirus Spreads |last=Ramzy |first=Austin |date=2020-01-30 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-01-30 |last2=Jr |first2=Donald G. McNeil |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On the date of the declaration, there were 7,818 cases confirmed globally, affecting 19 countries in five WHO regions.<ref>WHO Report (30 January 2020). {{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/situation-reports/20200130-sitrep-10-ncov.pdf?sfvrsn=d0b2e480_2 |title=Novel Coronavirus(2019-nCoV): Situation Report-10 |publisher=WHO |date=30 January 2020 |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov) |title=Statement on the second meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV) |publisher=WHO |date=30 January 2020 |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref> Previously, the WHO had held EC meetings on 22 and 23 January 2020 regarding the coronavirus pandemic,<ref name=Fifield23Jan2020>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/nine-dead-as-chinese-coronavirus-spreads-despite-efforts-to-contain-it/2020/01/22/1eaade72-3c6d-11ea-afe2-090eb37b60b1_story.html|title=Nine dead as Chinese coronavirus spreads, despite efforts to contain it|last=Fifield|first=Anna|last2=Sun|first2=Lena H. |date=23 January 2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Schnirring22Jan2020>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2020/01/who-decision-ncov-emergency-delayed-cases-spike|title=WHO decision on nCoV emergency delayed as cases spike|last=Schnirring|first=Lisa|date=22 January 2020|website=CIDRAP|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"WHO22Jan2020\">WHO Statement (22 January 2020). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-statement-on-ihr-emergency-committee-on-novel-coronavirus|title=WHO Director-General's statement on IHR Emergency Committee on Novel Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=22 January 2020|website=www.who.int|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> but it was determined that it was too early to declare a PHEIC  at that time given the lack of necessary data and the (then) scale of global impact.<ref name=\"StatNews\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/01/23/who-declines-to-declare-china-virus-outbreak-a-global-health-emergency/|title=WHO declines to declare China virus outbreak a global health emergency|last=Joseph|first=Andrew|date=23 January 2020|website=STAT|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=WHO23Jan2020>WHO Statement (23 January 2020). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/23-01-2020-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus 2019 (n-CoV) on 23 January 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=www.who.int|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> The WHO recognized the spread of [[COVID-19]] as a [[pandemic]] on 11 March 2020.<ref name=\"WHOpandemic1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020|title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 \u2013 11 March 2020|date=20 March 2020|publisher=[[World Health Organization]]|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref> Europe, Iran, USA, South Korea and Japan reported a surging of cases and the total number quickly passed China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Operations Dashboard for ArcGIS|website=gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\nIn 2018, an examination of the first four declarations (2009\u20132016) showed that the WHO was noted to be more effective in responding to international health emergencies, and that the international system in dealing with these emergencies was \"robust\".<ref name=\"Hunger2018\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/oso/9780198828945.001.0001/oso-9780198828945-chapter-4|title=Coping with Public Health Emergencies of International Concern|volume=1|last=Hunger|first=Iris|date=2018|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=9780191867422|location=|pages=|language=en-US|doi=10.1093/oso/9780198828945.003.0004}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nAnother review of the first four declarations, with the exception of wild polio, demonstrated that responses were varied. Severe outbreaks, or those that threatened larger numbers of people, did not receive a swift PHEIC declaration, and the study hypothesized that responses were quicker when American citizens were infected and when the emergencies did not coincide with holidays.<ref name=Hoffman2018/>\n\n==Non-declarations==\n[[File:Mers-virus-3D-image.jpg|thumb|MERS-coronavirus]]\n\n===2013 MERS===\nPHEIC was not invoked with the [[Middle Eastern Respiratory Syndrome]] (MERS) outbreak in 2013.<ref name=\"urlMERS - The Global Dispatch\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.theglobaldispatch.com/mers-does-not-constitute-a-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern-pheic-emergency-committee-32451/\n| title = MERS does not constitute a Public Health Emergency of International Concern (PHEIC): Emergency committee \u2013 The Global Dispatc\n| author =  Robert Herriman\n| date = 17 July 2013\n| publisher = The Global Dispatch\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref><ref name=\"urlWHO-2IHRECV-MERS-CoV\">{{cite web\n| url = http://centerforvaccineethicsandpolicy.net/2013/07/20/who-statement-second-meeting-of-the-ihr-emergency-committee-concerning-mers-cov-pheic-conditions-not-met/\n| title = WHO Statement: Second Meeting of the IHR Emergency Committee concerning MERS-CoV \u2013 PHEIC Conditions Not Met &#124; global vaccine ethics and policy\n| author = David R Curry\n| date = 20 July 2013\n| publisher = Center for Vaccine Ethics and Policy\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref> Originating in Saudi Arabia, MERS reached more than 24 countries and resulted in more than 580 deaths by 2015, although most cases were in hospital settings rather than sustained community spread. What constitutes a PHEIC has, as a result, been unclear.<ref name=Halabi2017/>\n\n== Non-infectious events ==\nPHEIC are not confined to only infectious diseases. It may cover events caused by chemical agents or radioactive materials.<ref name=Halabi2017/>\n\nThe emergence and spread of [[antimicrobial resistance]] may debatably constitute a PHEIC.<ref name=AMR>{{Cite web|url=https://medicalxpress.com/news/2011-04-international-health-antimicrobial-resistance.html|title=Can the International Health Regulations apply to antimicrobial resistance?|website=medicalxpress.com|language=en-us|access-date=15 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=Wernli2011>{{Cite journal|last=Wernli|first=Didier|last2=Haustein|first2=Thomas|last3=Conly|first3=John|last4=Carmeli|first4=Yehuda|last5=Kickbusch|first5=Ilona|last6=Harbarth|first6=Stephan|date=April 2011|title=A call for action: the application of The International Health Regulations to the global threat of antimicrobial resistance|journal=[[PLOS Medicine]]|volume=8|issue=4|pages=e1001022|doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001022|issn=1549-1676|pmc=3079636|pmid=21526227}}</ref><ref name=Kamradt-Scott2011>{{Cite journal|last=Kamradt-Scott|first=Adam|date=19 April 2011|title=A Public Health Emergency of International Concern? Response to a Proposal to Apply the International Health Regulations to Antimicrobial Resistance|journal=PLOS Medicine|language=en|volume=8|issue=4|pages=e1001021|doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001021|pmid=21526165|pmc=3080965|issn=1549-1676}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Biosecurity]]\n*[[Disease X]]\n*[[Notifiable disease]]\n*[[Public health emergency (United States)]]\n*[[State of emergency]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/20-12-2019-statement-o-the-twenty-third-ihr-emergency-committee-regarding-the-international-spread-of-poliovirus Statement of the Twenty-Third IHR Emergency Committee Regarding the International Spread of Poliovirus]. WHO 7 January 2020\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Politics|Viruses|right=yes}}\n*[https://www.who.int/features/qa/emergency-committees/en/ International Health Regulations and Emergency Committees]. www.who.int \n\n{{PHEIC}}\n{{Zika}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:Public Health Emergency of International Concern| ]]\n[[Category:Global health]]\n[[Category:Health law]]\n[[Category:World Health Organization]]\n[[Category:Emergency management]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Formal declaration by the World Health Organization}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:World Health Organization Logo.svg|thumb|Logo of the World Health Organization, the authority which declares PHEIC]]\nA '''Public Health Emergency of International Concern''' ('''PHEIC''', pronounced \"fake\"<ref name=Van-Tam2010>{{Cite book|last=Van-Tam|first=Jonathan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_IYYr9cjE30C&pg=PA195|title=Introduction to Pandemic Influenza|last2=Sellwood|first2=Chloe|date=2010|publisher=CABI|location=Wallingford, Oxford|isbn=978-1-84593-625-9|language=en}}</ref>) is a formal declaration by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) of \"an extraordinary event which is determined to constitute a public health risk to other States through the international spread of disease and to potentially require a coordinated international response\", formulated when a situation arises that is \"serious, sudden, unusual or unexpected\", which \"carries implications for public health beyond the affected state's national border\" and \"may require immediate international action\".<ref name=WHOIHR1>WHO Q&A (19 June 2019). {{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/features/qa/emergency-committees/en/|title= International Health Regulations and Emergency Committees|website=WHO|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref> Under the 2005 [[International Health Regulations]] (IHR), states have a legal duty to respond promptly to a PHEIC.<ref name=\"urlInside Justice-WHO-PHEIC\"/> The declaration is publicized by an Emergency Committee (EC) made up of international experts operating under the IHR (2005),<ref name=\"WHO-IHR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/ihr/about/en/|title=Strengthening health security by implementing the International Health Regulations (2005); About IHR|publisher=WHO|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref> which was developed following the [[Timeline of the SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak]] of 2002\u201303.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" />\n\nSince 2009 there have been six PHEIC declarations:<ref name=\"WashPost2016\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/02/02/who-declared-a-public-health-emergency-about-zikas-effects-here-are-three-takeaways/|title=WHO declared a public health emergency about Zika's effects. Here are three takeaways|last=Pillinger|first=Mara|date=2 February 2016|access-date=19 June 2019|work=Washington Post}}{{subscription required}}</ref> the [[2009 flu pandemic|2009 H1N1 (or swine flu) pandemic]], the [[Poliomyelitis eradication#2011\u20132015|2014 polio declaration]], the [[2014 West Africa Ebola outbreak|2014 outbreak of Ebola in Western Africa]], the [[2015\u201316 Zika virus epidemic]],<ref name=\"Hunger2018\"/> the ongoing [[Kivu Ebola epidemic|2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola epidemic]],<ref name=\"WHO18Oct2019\"/> and the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], declared a PHEIC by the Director-General on 30 January 2020.<ref name=\"WHOStatement30January2020\">WHO Statement (31 January 2020). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|title=Statement on the second meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|last=|first=|date=31 January 2020|website=World Health Organisation|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref> The recommendations are temporary and require reviews every three months.<ref name=WHOIHR1/>\n\n[[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]], [[smallpox]], [[wild type]] [[poliomyelitis]], and any new subtype of [[human influenza]] are automatically PHEICs and thus do not require an IHR decision to declare them as such.<ref name=Hall2018>{{cite book|author1=Mark A. Hall|author2=David Orentlicher|author3=Mary Anne Bobinski|author4=Nicholas Bagley|author5=I. Glenn Cohen|title=Health Care Law and Ethics|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mwJODwAAQBAJ&pg=PA908|edition=9th|date=26 February 2018|publisher=Wolters Kluwer |location=New York|isbn=978-1-4548-8180-3|page=908|chapter=8. Public Health Law}}</ref> A PHEIC is not confined to infectious diseases, and may cover an emergency caused by exposure to a chemical agent or radioactive material.<ref name=Halabi2017>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nvzmDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA110 |title=Global Management of Infectious Disease After Ebola|last=Halabi|first=Sam F.|last2=Crowley|first2=Jeffrey S.|last3=Gostin|first3=Lawrence Ogalthorpe|date=2017|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=9780190604882|location=|pages=110|language=en}}</ref> In any case within its ambit, it is a \"call to action\" and \"last resort\" measure.<ref name=\"Rull2015\">{{Cite journal|last=Rull|first=Monica|last2=Kickbusch|first2=Ilona|last3=Lauer|first3=Helen|date=8 December 2015|title=Policy Debate {{!}} International Responses to Global Epidemics: Ebola and Beyond|journal=International Development Policy|language=en|volume=6|issue=2|doi=10.4000/poldev.2178|issn=1663-9375}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nMultiple surveillance and response systems exist worldwide for the early detection and effective response to contain the spread of disease. Time delays still occur for two main reasons, however. The first is the delay between the [[index case|first case]] and the confirmation of the outbreak by the healthcare system, allayed by good surveillance via data collection, evaluation, and organisation. The second is when there is a delay between the detection of the outbreak and widespread recognition and declaration of it as an international concern.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> The declaration is promulgated by an Emergency Committee (EC) made up of international experts operating under the IHR (2005),<ref name=\"WHO-IHR2\"/> which was developed following the [[Timeline of the SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak]] of 2002/2003.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> Between 2009 and 2016, there were four PHEIC declarations.<ref name=\"WashPost2016\"/> The fifth was the 2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola epidemic which was announced on 17 July 2019.<ref name=\"WHO18Oct2019\"/> The sixth is the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 novel coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"WHOStatement30January2020\"/> Under the 2005 [[International Health Regulations]] (IHR), States have a legal duty to respond promptly to a PHEIC.<ref name=\"urlInside Justice-WHO-PHEIC\"/>\n\n==Definition==\nPHEIC is defined as; <blockquote>an extraordinary event which is determined to constitute a public health risk to other States through the international spread of disease and to potentially require a coordinated international response<ref name=WHO2016>WHO Regulations (2005). {{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/ihr/annex_2/en/|title=WHO {{!}} Annex 2 of the International Health Regulations (2005)|website=WHO|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThis definition designates a [[public health crisis]] of potentially global reach and implies a situation that is \"serious, sudden, unusual or unexpected\", which may necessitate immediate international action.<ref name=WHO2016/><ref name=Exter2015>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FhMACwAAQBAJ&pg=PA540|title=International Health Law and Ethics: Basic Documents|last=Exter|first=Andr\u00e9 den|date=2015|publisher=Maklu|isbn=9789046607923|edition=3rd|series=|location=|pages=540|language=en|chapter=Part VI Public Health; Chapter 1.1 International Health Regulations (2005)}}</ref>\n\nIt is a \"call to action\" and \"last resort\" measure.<ref name=\"Rull2015\"/>\n\n==Reporting a potential concern==\nWHO Member States have 24 hours within which to report potential PHEIC events to the WHO.<ref name=Hall2018/> It does not have to be a member State that reports a potential outbreak, hence reports to the WHO can also be received informally.<ref name=Davies2015/>\nUnder the IHR (2005), ways to detect, evaluate, notify and report events were ascertained by all countries in order to avoid PHEICs. The response to public health risks was also decided.<ref name=Rull2015/>\n\nThe IHR decision algorithm assists WHO Member States in deciding whether a potential PHEIC exists and the WHO should be notified. The WHO should be notified if any two of the four following questions are affirmed:<ref name=Hall2018/>\n*Is the public health impact of the event serious?\n*Is the event unusual or unexpected?\n*Is there a significant risk for international spread?\n*Is there a significant risk for international travel or trade restrictions?\n\nThe PHEIC criteria include a list of diseases that are always notifiable.<ref name=Davies2015>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=kvvVBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA61 |title=Disease Diplomacy: International Norms and Global Health Security|last=Davies|first=Sara E.|last2=Kamradt-Scott|first2=Adam|last3=Rushton|first3=Simon|date=2015|publisher=[[Johns Hopkins University Press]]|isbn=9781421416489|language=en}}</ref> [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]], [[smallpox]], [[wild type]] [[poliomyelitis]] and any new subtype of [[human influenza]] are always a PHEIC and do not require an IHR decision to declare them as such.<ref name=WHO2016/>\n\nQuotidian epidemics which public attention do fulfill the criteria to be a PHEIC.<ref name=\"Rull2015\"/> EC's were not convened for the [[2010s Haiti cholera outbreak|cholera outbreak in Haiti]], [[Ghouta chemical attack|chemical weapons use in Syria]] or the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|Fukushima nuclear disaster in Japan]], for example.<ref name=Halabi2017/><ref name=Gostin2016/>\n\nFurther assessment is required for diseases which are prone to [[pandemic]]s, including but not limited to [[cholera]], [[pneumonic plague]], [[yellow fever]], and viral hemorrhagic fevers.<ref name=Gostin2016/>\n\nA declaration of a PHEIC may appear as an economic burden to the state facing the epidemic. Incentives to declare an epidemic are lacking and the PHEIC can be seen as placing limitations on trade in countries that are already struggling.<ref name=Rull2015/>\n\n==Emergency committee==\nIn order to declare a PHEIC, the [[WHO#Director-General|WHO Director-General]] is required to take into account factors which include the risk to human health and international spread as well as advice from an internationally made up committee of experts, the IHR Emergency Committee (EC), one of which should be an expert nominated by the State within whose region the event arises.<ref name=WHOIHR1/> Rather than being a standing committee, the EC is created [[ad hoc]].<ref name=Kamradt-Scott2019>{{Cite journal|last=Kamradt-Scott|first=Adam|last2=Eccleston-Turner|first2=Mark|date=1 April 2019|title=Transparency in IHR emergency committee decision making: the case for reform|url=https://gh.bmj.com/content/4/2/e001618|journal=British Medical Journal Global Health|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=e001618|doi=10.1136/bmjgh-2019-001618|pmid=31139463|pmc=6509695|issn=2059-7908|via=}}</ref>\n\nUntil 2011, the names of IHR EC members were not publicly disclosed. These members are selected according to the disease in question and the nature of the event. The Director-General takes the EC's advice following their technical assessment of the crisis using legal criteria and a predetermined algorithm after a review of all available data on the event. Upon declaration, the EC then makes recommendations on what actions the Director-General and Member States should take to address the crisis.<ref name=Kamradt-Scott2019/> The recommendations are temporary and require three-monthly reviews.<ref name=WHOIHR1/>\n\n==Declarations==\n[[File:H1N1 influenza virus.jpg|thumb|upright|H1N1 influenza virus]]\n\n===2009 swine flu declaration===\nIn the spring of 2009, a novel influenza A (H1N1) virus emerged. It was detected first in the United States of America and spread quickly across the United States and the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/flu/pandemic-resources/2009-h1n1-pandemic.html|title=2009 H1N1 Pandemic|last=CDC|date=2019-06-11|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> On 26 April 2009,<ref name=H1N12009WHO>{{Cite book|url=http://apps.who.int/gb/ebwha/pdf_files/WHA64/A64_10-en.pdf|title=Implementation of the International Health Regulations (2005), Report of the Review Committee on the Functioning of the International Health Regulations (2005) in relation to Pandemic (H1N1) 2009|last=Director-General|publisher=WHO|year=2009|isbn=|location=|pages=118}}</ref> more than one month after its first emergence,<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\">{{Cite journal|last=Hoffman|first=Steven J.|last2=Silverberg|first2=Sarah L.|date=18 January 2018|title=Delays in Global Disease Outbreak Responses: Lessons from H1N1, Ebola, and Zika|journal=[[American Journal of Public Health]]|volume=108|issue=3|pages=329\u2013333|doi=10.2105/AJPH.2017.304245|pmid=29345996|pmc=5803810|issn=0090-0036}}</ref> the first PHEIC was declared when the [[2009 flu pandemic|H1N1 (or swine flu) pandemic]] was still in [[Influenza pandemic#Phases|Phase Three]].<ref name=\"urlInside Justice-WHO-PHEIC\">{{cite web| url = http://www.insidejustice.com/intl/2009/04/30/swine_flu_who_pheic/| title = Inside Justice &#124; Swine Flu: Legal Obligations and Consequences When the World Health Organization Declares a \"Public Health Emergency of International Concern\"| author =  Renee Dopplick| date = 29 April 2009| accessdate = 6 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"urlWHO | Swine influenza\">{{cite web| url = http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2009/h1n1_20090425/en/\n| title = Swine influenza| author = Margaret Chan | date = 25 April 2009| publisher = [[World Health Organization]]| accessdate = 6 June 2014| author-link = Margaret Chan}}</ref><ref name=\"urlWHO | Swine flu illness in the United States and Mexico - update 2\">{{cite web| url = http://www.who.int/csr/don/2009_04_26/en/| title = Swine flu illness in the United States and Mexico \u2013 update 2| author = | date = 26 April 2009| publisher = [[World Health Organization]]| accessdate = 6 June 2014}}</ref> On the same day, within three hours the WHO web site received almost two million visits, necessitating the pandemic's own dedicated pandemic influenza web site.<ref name=H1N12009WHO/> At the time H1N1 had been declared a PHEIC, it had so far occurred in only three countries.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> Declaring H1N1 a PHEIC has therefore been argued as fueling public fear.<ref name=Gostin2016>{{Cite journal|last=Gostin|first=Lawrence O.|last2=Katz|first2=Rebeccas|date=June 2016|title=The International Health Regulations: The Governing Framework for Global Health Security|journal=The Milbank Quarterly|volume=94|issue=2|pages=264\u2013313|doi=10.1111/1468-0009.12186|pmid=27166578|pmc=4911720}}</ref> However, a 2013 study sponsored by the WHO estimated that although the H1N1 pandemic was similar in magnitude to seasonal influenza, it resulted in the loss of more life-years due to a shift toward mortality among persons less than 65 years of age.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Simonsen |first=Lone |last2=Spreeuwenberg |first2=Peter |last3=Lustig |first3=Roger |last4=Taylor |first4=Robert J. |last5=Fleming |first5=Douglas M. |last6=Kroneman |first6=Madelon |last7=Van Kerkhove |first7=Maria D. |last8=Mounts |first8=Anthony W. |last9=Paget |first9=W. John |last10=Hay |first10=Simon I. |title=Global Mortality Estimates for the 2009 Influenza Pandemic from the GLaMOR Project: A Modeling Study |journal=[[PLOS Medicine]] |date=26 November 2013 |volume=10 |issue=11 |pages=e1001558 |doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001558 |pmid=24302890 |pmc=3841239}}</ref>\n\n===2014 polio declaration===\nThe second PHEIC was the [[Poliomyelitis eradication#2011\u20132015|2014 polio declaration]], issued in May 2014 with the resurgence of [[poliomyelitis|wild polio]] after its near-eradication, deemed \"an extraordinary event\".<ref name=\"urlWHO-IHREC-wild poliovirus\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2014/polio-20140505/en/\n| title = WHO &#124; WHO statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations Emergency Committee concerning the international spread of wild poliovirus\n| author = \n| date = 5 May 2014\n| publisher = [[World Health Organization]]\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref><ref name=\"urlNewScientist-polio cases surge-2014-0505\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn25518-global-emergency-declared-as-polio-cases-surge.html\n| title = Global emergency declared as polio cases surge \u2013 health \u2013 05 May 2014 \u2013 New Scientist\n| first =  Debora\n| last = MacKenzie\n| date = 5 May 2014\n| publisher = New Scientist\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref>\n\nGlobal eradication was deemed to be at risk with small numbers of cases in Afghanistan, Pakistan, and Nigeria.<ref name=Gostin2016/>\n\nIn October 2019, continuing cases of wild polio in Pakistan and Afghanistan, in addition to new vaccine-derived cases in Africa and Asia, was reviewed and remains a PHEIC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/10/news-scan-oct-04-2019|title=News Scan: Polio in Pakistan|last=|first=|date=4 October 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> It was extended on 11 December 2019.<ref name=THP11Dec2019>{{Cite web|url=https://travelhealthpro.org.uk/news/483/polio-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern|title=NaTHNaC - Polio: Public Health Emergency of International Concern|last=|first=|date=|website=TravelHealthPro|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2014 Ebola declaration===\nConfirmed cases of Ebola were being reported in Guinea and Liberia in March 2014 and Sierra Leone by May 2014. On Friday, 8 August 2014, following the occurrence of Ebola in the United States and Europe and with the already intense transmission ongoing in three other countries for months,<ref name=Rull2015/> the WHO declared its third PHEIC in response to the [[2014 West Africa Ebola outbreak|outbreak of Ebola in Western Africa]].<ref name=WHO2014>{{Cite web|url=http://www.euro.who.int/en/health-topics/emergencies/pages/news/news/2014/08/ebola-outbreak-in-west-africa-declared-a-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern|title=Ebola outbreak in West Africa declared a public health emergency of international concern|date=8 August 2014|website=www.euro.who.int|language=en|access-date=3 June 2019}}</ref> Later, one review showed that a direct impact of this epidemic on America escalated a PHEIC declaration.<ref name=\"Hoffman2018\" /> It was the first PHEIC in a resource-poor setting.<ref name=Rull2015/>\n\n===2016 Zika virus declaration===\nOn 1 February 2016, the WHO declared its fourth PHEIC in response to clusters of [[microcephaly]] and [[Guillain\u2013Barr\u00e9 syndrome]] in the [[Americas]], which at the time were suspected to be associated with the ongoing [[2015\u201316 Zika virus epidemic]].<ref>WHO (1 February 2016). [http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2016/emergency-committee-zika-microcephaly/en/ WHO Director-General summarizes the outcome of the Emergency Committee on Zika]</ref> Later research and evidence bore out these concerns; in April, the WHO stated that \"there is scientific consensus that Zika virus is a cause of microcephaly and Guillain\u2013Barr\u00e9 syndrome.\"<ref name=\"WHO SitRep 7 Apr 2016\">{{cite web | url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/204961/1/zikasitrep_7Apr2016_eng.pdf?ua=1 | title=Zika Virus Microcephaly And Guillain\u2013Barr\u00e9 Syndrome Situation Report | publisher=World Health Organization | date=7 April 2016 | accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref>  This was the first time a PHEIC was declared for a [[Mosquito-borne disease|mosquito\u2010borne disease]].<ref name=Gostin2016/> This declaration was lifted on 18 November 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fifth meeting of the Emergency Committee under the International Health Regulations (2005) regarding microcephaly, other neurological disorders and Zika virus|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2016/zika-fifth-ec/en/|website=World Health Organization|publisher=WHO|accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola declaration ===\nIn October 2018 and then later in April 2019, the WHO did not consider the [[2018\u201320 Kivu Ebola epidemic]] to be a PHEIC.<ref name=\"Green20April2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Green|first=Andrew|date=20 April 2019|title=DR Congo Ebola outbreak not given PHEIC designation|journal=The Lancet|volume=393|issue=10181|pages=1586|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(19)30893-1|pmid=31007190}}</ref><ref name=\"PHEICApril2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/12-04-2019-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-for-ebola-virus-disease-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo-on-12th-april-2019|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee for Ebola virus disease in the Democratic Republic of the Congo on 12th April 2019|date=12 April 2019|publisher=World Health Organization|accessdate=13 June 2019}}</ref> The decision was controversial, with [[Michael Osterholm]], director of the [[Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy]] (CIDRAP) responding with disappointment and describing the situation as \"an Ebola gas can sitting in DRC that's just waiting for a match to hit it\",<ref name=\"Cohen2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2019/04/ebola-outbreak-congo-still-not-international-crisis-who-decides|title=Ebola outbreak in Congo still not an international crisis, WHO decides|last=Cohen|first=Jon|last2=2019|date=12 April 2019|website=Science {{!}} AAAS|language=en|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> while the WHO panel were unanimous that declaring it a PHEIC would not give any added benefit.<ref name=\"Cohen2019\" /> The advice against declaring a PHEIC in October 2018 and April 2019, despite the criteria for doing so appearing to be met on both occasions has led to the transparency of the IHR EC coming into question. The language used in the statements for the Kivu Ebola epidemic has been noted to be different. In October 2018, the EC stated \"a PHEIC should not be declared at this time\". However, in the 13 previously declined proposals for declaring a PHEIC, the resultant statements quoted \"the conditions for a PHEIC are not currently met\" and \"does not constitute a PHEIC\". In April 2019, they stated that \"there is no added benefit to declaring a PHEIC at this stage\", a notion that is not part of the PHEIC criteria laid down in the IHR.<ref name=\"Kamradt-Scott2019\" /><ref name=\"Lancet2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Lancet|first=The|date=25 May 2019|title=Acknowledging the limits of public health solutions|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(19)31183-3/abstract|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=393|issue=10186|pages=2100|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(19)31183-3|issn=0140-6736|pmid=31226033}}</ref>\n\nAfter confirmed cases of Ebola in neighbouring Uganda in June 2019, [[Tedros Adhanom]], the Director-General of the WHO, announced that the third meeting of a group of experts would be held on 14 June 2019 to assess whether the Ebola spread had become a PHEIC.<ref name=\"Hunt2019\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/06/12/health/ebola-outbreak-death-uganda-africa-intl-bn/index.html|title=Ebola outbreak enters 'truly frightening phase' as it turns deadly in Uganda|last=Hunt|first=Katie|website=CNN|language=en|accessdate=12 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes14June2019\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/world/africa/ebola-uganda-congo.html|title=Boy, 5, and Grandmother Die in Uganda as More Ebola Cases Emerge|last=Gladstone|first=Rick|date=12 June 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=14 June 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The conclusion was that while the outbreak was a health emergency in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] (DRC) and the region, it does not meet all the three criteria for a PHEIC.<ref name=\"WHO14June2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/14-06-2019-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-for-ebola-virus-disease-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee for Ebola virus disease in the Democratic Republic of the Congo on 14 June 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=World Health Organization|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 June 2019}}</ref> Despite the number of deaths reaching 1,405 by 11 June 2019 and 1,440 by 17 June 2019, the reason for not declaring a PHIEC was that the overall risk of international spread was deemed to be low, and the risk of damaging the economy of the DRC high.<ref name=\"SoucharyJune2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/06/ebola-case-counts-spike-again-drc|title=Ebola case counts spike again in DRC|last=Souchary|first=Stephanie|date=17 June 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=24 June 2019}}</ref> Adhanom also stated that declaring a PHEIC would be an inappropriate way to raise money for the epidemic.<ref name=\"CIDRAP16July2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/07/who-will-take-ebola-emergency-declaration-question-fourth-time|title=WHO will take up Ebola emergency declaration question for a fourth time|last=Soucheray|first=Stephanie|last2=2019|date=16 July 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=17 July 2019}}</ref> Following a visit to the DRC in July 2019, [[Rory Stewart]], the UK's [[Department for International Development|DfID]] minister, called for the WHO to declare it an emergency.<ref name=\"Wintour9July2019\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/07/declare-ebola-outbreak-in-drc-an-emergency-says-uks-rory-stewart|title=Declare Ebola outbreak in DRC an emergency, says UK's Rory Stewart|last=Wintour|first=Patrick|date=7 July 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=9 July 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nAcknowledging a high risk of spread to the capital of North Kivu, [[Goma]], a call for a PHEIC declaration was published on 10 July 2019 in the ''[[Washington Post]]'' by [[Daniel R. Lucey|Daniel Lucey]] and [[Ron Klain]] (the former US [[Ebola response coordinator]]). They stated that  \"in the absence of a trajectory toward extinguishing the outbreak, the opposite path\u2014severe escalation\u2014remains possible. The risk of the disease moving into nearby Goma, Congo\u2014a city of 1 million residents with an international airport \u2014or crossing into the massive refugee camps in South Sudan is mounting. With a limited number of vaccine doses remaining, either would be a catastrophe\".<ref name=\"Soucheray11July2019\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/07/three-more-health-workers-infected-ebola-outbreak|title=Three more health workers infected in Ebola outbreak|last=Soucheray|first=Stephanie|date=11 July 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Klain10July2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/its-time-to-declare-a-public-health-emergency-on-ebola/2019/07/10/c77641fc-a327-11e9-b732-41a79c2551bf_story.html|title=Opinion {{!}} It's time to declare a public health emergency on Ebola|last=Klain|first=Ronald A.|last2=Lucey|first2=Daniel|date=10 July 2019|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref> Four days later, on 14 July 2019, a case of Ebola was confirmed in Goma, which has an international airport and a highly mobile population. Subsequently, the WHO announced a reconvening of a fourth EC meeting on 17 July 2019, when they officially announced it \"a regional emergency, and by no means a global threat\" and declared it as a PHEIC, without restrictions on trade or travel.<ref name=\"WHONewsRelease17July2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/17-07-2019-ebola-outbreak-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo-declared-a-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern|title=Ebola outbreak in the Democratic Republic of the Congo declared a Public Health Emergency of International Concern|last=|first=|date=2019-07-17|website=World Health Organization|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref><ref name=BBCNews17July2019>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-49025298|title=Ebola outbreak declared public health emergency|last=|first=|date=17 July 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=17 July 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> In response to the declaration, the president of the DRC, together with an expert committee led by a virologist, took responsibility for directly supervising action, while in protest of the declaration, health minister, [[Oly Ilunga Kalenga]] resigned.<ref name=Schnirring22July2019>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/07/drc-health-minister-resigns-after-government-takes-ebola-reins|title=DRC health minister resigns after government takes Ebola reins|last=Schnirring|first=Lisa|date=22 July 2019|website=CIDRAP|language=en|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> A review of the PHEIC had been planned at a fifth meeting of the EC on 10 October 2019<ref name=9Oct2019>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/10/response-resumes-following-security-problems-drc-ebola-hot-spot|title=Response resumes following security problems in DRC Ebola hot spot|last=Schnirring|first=Lisa|last2=9 October 2019|date=|website=CIDRAP|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> and as of 18 October 2019, it continues to be a PHEIC.<ref name=\"WHO18Oct2019\">WHO Statement (18 October 2019). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/18-10-2019-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-for-ebola-virus-disease-in-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee for Ebola virus disease in the Democratic Republic of the Congo on 18 October 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=www.who.int|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 coronavirus pandemic (COVID-19) ===\n[[File:2019-nCoV-CDC-23312.png|thumb|right|Morphology of SARS-CoV-2]]\nOn 30 January 2020, the WHO declared the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|outbreak of COVID-19]], centered on [[Wuhan]] in [[central China]], a PHEIC.<ref name=\"WHOStatement30January2020\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/30/health/coronavirus-world-health-organization.html |title=W.H.O. Declares Global Emergency as the new Coronavirus Spreads |last=Ramzy |first=Austin |date=2020-01-30 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-01-30 |last2=Jr |first2=Donald G. McNeil |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> On the date of the declaration, there were 7,818 cases confirmed globally, affecting 19 countries in five WHO regions.<ref>WHO Report (30 January 2020). {{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/docs/default-source/coronaviruse/situation-reports/20200130-sitrep-10-ncov.pdf?sfvrsn=d0b2e480_2 |title=Novel Coronavirus(2019-nCoV): Situation Report-10 |publisher=WHO |date=30 January 2020 |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov) |title=Statement on the second meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV) |publisher=WHO |date=30 January 2020 |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref> Previously, the WHO had held EC meetings on 22 and 23 January 2020 regarding the coronavirus pandemic,<ref name=Fifield23Jan2020>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/nine-dead-as-chinese-coronavirus-spreads-despite-efforts-to-contain-it/2020/01/22/1eaade72-3c6d-11ea-afe2-090eb37b60b1_story.html|title=Nine dead as Chinese coronavirus spreads, despite efforts to contain it|last=Fifield|first=Anna|last2=Sun|first2=Lena H. |date=23 January 2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Schnirring22Jan2020>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2020/01/who-decision-ncov-emergency-delayed-cases-spike|title=WHO decision on nCoV emergency delayed as cases spike|last=Schnirring|first=Lisa|date=22 January 2020|website=CIDRAP|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"WHO22Jan2020\">WHO Statement (22 January 2020). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-statement-on-ihr-emergency-committee-on-novel-coronavirus|title=WHO Director-General's statement on IHR Emergency Committee on Novel Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=22 January 2020|website=www.who.int|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> but it was determined that it was too early to declare a PHEIC  at that time given the lack of necessary data and the (then) scale of global impact.<ref name=\"StatNews\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/01/23/who-declines-to-declare-china-virus-outbreak-a-global-health-emergency/|title=WHO declines to declare China virus outbreak a global health emergency|last=Joseph|first=Andrew|date=23 January 2020|website=STAT|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=WHO23Jan2020>WHO Statement (23 January 2020). {{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/23-01-2020-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus 2019 (n-CoV) on 23 January 2020|last=|first=|date=|website=www.who.int|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> The WHO recognized the spread of [[COVID-19]] as a [[pandemic]] on 11 March 2020.<ref name=\"WHOpandemic1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020|title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 \u2013 11 March 2020|date=20 March 2020|publisher=[[World Health Organization]]|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref> Europe, Iran, USA, South Korea and Japan reported a surging of cases and the total number quickly passed China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Operations Dashboard for ArcGIS|website=gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\nIn 2018, an examination of the first four declarations (2009\u20132016) showed that the WHO was noted to be more effective in responding to international health emergencies, and that the international system in dealing with these emergencies was \"robust\".<ref name=\"Hunger2018\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/oso/9780198828945.001.0001/oso-9780198828945-chapter-4|title=Coping with Public Health Emergencies of International Concern|volume=1|last=Hunger|first=Iris|date=2018|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|isbn=9780191867422|location=|pages=|language=en-US|doi=10.1093/oso/9780198828945.003.0004}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nAnother review of the first four declarations, with the exception of wild polio, demonstrated that responses were varied. Severe outbreaks, or those that threatened larger numbers of people, did not receive a swift PHEIC declaration, and the study hypothesized that responses were quicker when American citizens were infected and when the emergencies did not coincide with holidays.<ref name=Hoffman2018/>\n\n==Non-declarations==\n[[File:Mers-virus-3D-image.jpg|thumb|MERS-coronavirus]]\n\n===2013 MERS===\nPHEIC was not invoked with the [[Middle Eastern Respiratory Syndrome]] (MERS) outbreak in 2013.<ref name=\"urlMERS - The Global Dispatch\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.theglobaldispatch.com/mers-does-not-constitute-a-public-health-emergency-of-international-concern-pheic-emergency-committee-32451/\n| title = MERS does not constitute a Public Health Emergency of International Concern (PHEIC): Emergency committee \u2013 The Global Dispatc\n| author =  Robert Herriman\n| date = 17 July 2013\n| publisher = The Global Dispatch\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref><ref name=\"urlWHO-2IHRECV-MERS-CoV\">{{cite web\n| url = http://centerforvaccineethicsandpolicy.net/2013/07/20/who-statement-second-meeting-of-the-ihr-emergency-committee-concerning-mers-cov-pheic-conditions-not-met/\n| title = WHO Statement: Second Meeting of the IHR Emergency Committee concerning MERS-CoV \u2013 PHEIC Conditions Not Met &#124; global vaccine ethics and policy\n| author = David R Curry\n| date = 20 July 2013\n| publisher = Center for Vaccine Ethics and Policy\n| accessdate = 6 June 2014\n}}</ref> Originating in Saudi Arabia, MERS reached more than 24 countries and resulted in more than 580 deaths by 2015, although most cases were in hospital settings rather than sustained community spread. What constitutes a PHEIC has, as a result, been unclear.<ref name=Halabi2017/>\n\n== Non-infectious events ==\nPHEIC are not confined to only infectious diseases. It may cover events caused by chemical agents or radioactive materials.<ref name=Halabi2017/>\n\nThe emergence and spread of [[antimicrobial resistance]] may debatably constitute a PHEIC.<ref name=AMR>{{Cite web|url=https://medicalxpress.com/news/2011-04-international-health-antimicrobial-resistance.html|title=Can the International Health Regulations apply to antimicrobial resistance?|website=medicalxpress.com|language=en-us|access-date=15 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=Wernli2011>{{Cite journal|last=Wernli|first=Didier|last2=Haustein|first2=Thomas|last3=Conly|first3=John|last4=Carmeli|first4=Yehuda|last5=Kickbusch|first5=Ilona|last6=Harbarth|first6=Stephan|date=April 2011|title=A call for action: the application of The International Health Regulations to the global threat of antimicrobial resistance|journal=[[PLOS Medicine]]|volume=8|issue=4|pages=e1001022|doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001022|issn=1549-1676|pmc=3079636|pmid=21526227}}</ref><ref name=Kamradt-Scott2011>{{Cite journal|last=Kamradt-Scott|first=Adam|date=19 April 2011|title=A Public Health Emergency of International Concern? Response to a Proposal to Apply the International Health Regulations to Antimicrobial Resistance|journal=PLOS Medicine|language=en|volume=8|issue=4|pages=e1001021|doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.1001021|pmid=21526165|pmc=3080965|issn=1549-1676}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Biosecurity]]\n*