r, politician, martyr\n*[[Nazmul Hossain Shanto]] (born 1998), Bangladeshi cricketer\n\n==See also==\n*[[Nazul]]\n*{{in title}}\n\n{{given name}}\n", "name_user": "Jo-Jo Eumerus", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Siddique Nazmul Alamclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazmul"}
{"title_page": "Brafferton (building)", "text_new": "[[Image:BraffertonBuildingin2007.jpg|thumb|250px|The Brafferton, seen from Jamestown Road]]\nThe '''Brafferton''', built in 1723, is located southeast of the Sir Christopher [[Wren Building]], facing the President's House on the campus of the [[College of William and Mary]] in [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]], [[Virginia]].\n\n==History==\nThe Brafferton was constructed in 1723, likely by [[Henry Cary, Jr.]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lounsbury|first1=Carl|title=Henry Cary (d. by 1750)|url=http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Cary_Henry_d_by_1750|publisher=Encyclopedia Virginia|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref> to house the College's [[Native Americans in the United States|Indian]] school, which was endowed by funds from an estate purchased by the charity of [[Robert Boyle]], the noted English scientist. Income from Brafferton Manor in [[Yorkshire]], [[England]], designated for charitable and pious purposes, was used to \"civilize\" Indian youth, prepare them for Anglican priesthood \u2014 and produce interpreters and cultural liaisons who could aid Britain's colonial expansion. The undertaking of producing Indian ministers met with little success, except among the Pamunkey. Virginia's efforts to encourage allied and neighboring tribes to send Indian youth to Williamsburg were more successful, and several Brafferton students were key players in the late eighteenth century wars of North America. However, during the [[American Revolution]], income from the Boyle estate was interrupted, and the teenage students mostly engaged in the conflict, the last leaving during the fall of 1778. Boyle monies were reinvested in the College following the Revolution, but discontinued after 1784, partially as a result of a lengthy court case involving the trustees of the Boyle Charity and the College of William & Mary. After the College lost the chancery case, the Indian school was abandoned, and the Boyle money was redirecting to the Caribbean, and still later, to Canada.  \n\nThe Brafferton was damaged during the [[American Civil War]] and the College spent $3,000 for repairs. Throughout the years, the building served as a residence for professors, a dormitory for students, an armory for the Wise Light Infantry, and an alumni office.  Additionally, it has temporarily housed other offices, fine arts classes, and even the Music Department for a short period of time.  Since 1985, the Brafferton has housed the offices of the president and the provost of the College. At the request of the Governor's advisory Council on Indians, a state historical marker was erected on the Brafferton grounds in 2005.\n\nThe building was first refurbished in 1930-31 during the restoration of Colonial Williamsburg. It received additional renovation in 2010\u201313, a period in which the College of William & Mary established the Brafferton Legacy Group in conjunction with alumni from the school's tribal descendant communities, the Department of Anthropology, the College's American Indian Resource Center, Colonial Williamsburg's (CW) Department of Archaeology, and CW's American Indian Initiative. The College and CW hosted a ground blessing for the start of archaeological investigations at the Indian school, and several Pamunkey tribal members worked on the 2011-12 excavations. The building was rededicated in 2013 with opening remarks in the Cherokee language and honor songs, alongside greetings from the President of William & Mary and College Provost.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* University Archives Buildings File (2007).  ''Brafferton''.  Earl Gregg Swem Library, The College of William and Mary.\n* Virginia Vignettes - What Was the Brafferton School? [https://web.archive.org/web/20070827183434/http://www.virginiavignettes.org/]\n* The Brafferton- History.org [http://www.history.org/almanack/places/hb/hbbraff.cfm]\n\n{{The College of William & Mary}}\n{{coord |display=title|37.270471|-76.708255}}\n\n[[Category:School buildings completed in 1723]]\n[[Category:College of William & Mary buildings]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:BraffertonBuildingin2007.jpg|thumb|250px|The Brafferton, seen from Jamestown Road]]\nThe '''Brafferton''', built in 1723, is located southeast of the Sir Christopher [[Wren Building]], facing the President's House on the campus of the [[College of William and Mary]] in [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]], [[Virginia]].\n\n==History==\nThe Brafferton was constructed in 1723, likely by [[Henry Cary, Jr.]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lounsbury|first1=Carl|title=Henry Cary (d. by 1750)|url=http://www.encyclopediavirginia.org/Cary_Henry_d_by_1750|publisher=Encyclopedia Virginia|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref> to house the College's [[Native Americans in the United States|Indian]] school, which was endowed by funds from an estate purchased by the charity of [[Robert Boyle]], the noted English scientist. Income from Brafferton Manor in [[Yorkshire]], [[England]], designated for charitable and pious purposes, was used to \"civilize\" Indian youth, prepare them for Anglican priesthood \u2014 and produce interpreters and cultural liaisons who could aid Britain's colonial expansion. The undertaking of producing Indian ministers met with little success, except among the Pamunkey. Virginia's efforts to encourage allied and neighboring tribes to send Indian youth to Williamsburg were more successful, and several Brafferton students were key players in the late eighteenth century wars of North America. However, during the [[American Revolution]], income from the Boyle estate was interrupted, and the teenage students mostly engaged in the conflict, the last leaving during the fall of 1778. Boyle monies were reinvested in the College following the Revolution, but discontinued after 1784, partially as a result of a lengthy court case involving the trustees of the Boyle Charity and the College of William & Mary. After the College lost the chancery case, the Indian school was abandoned, and the Boyle money was redirecting to the Caribbean, and still later, to Canada.  \n\nThe Brafferton was damaged during the [[American Civil War]] and the College spent $3,000 for repairs. Throughout the years, the building served as a residence for professors, a dormitory for students, an armory for the Wise Light Infantry, and an alumni office.  Additionally, it has temporarily housed other offices, fine arts classes, and even the Music Department for a short period of time.  Since 1985, the Brafferton has housed the offices of the president and the provost of the College. At the request of the Governor's advisory Council on Indians, a state historical marker was erected on the Brafferton grounds in 2005.\n\nThe building was first refurbished in 1930-31 during the restoration of Colonial Williamsburg. It received additional renovation in 2010-13, a period in which the College of William & Mary established the Brafferton Legacy Group in conjunction with alumni from the school's tribal descendant communities, the Department of Anthropology, the College's American Indian Resource Center, Colonial Williamsburg's (CW) Department of Archaeology, and CW's American Indian Initiative. The College and CW hosted a ground blessing for the start of archaeological investigations at the Indian school, and several Pamunkey tribal members worked on the 2011-12 excavations. The building was rededicated in 2013 with opening remarks in the Cherokee language and honor songs, alongside greetings from the President of William & Mary and College Provost.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* University Archives Buildings File (2007).  ''Brafferton''.  Earl Gregg Swem Library, The College of William and Mary.\n* Virginia Vignettes - What Was the Brafferton School? [https://web.archive.org/web/20070827183434/http://www.virginiavignettes.org/]\n* The Brafferton- History.org [http://www.history.org/almanack/places/hb/hbbraff.cfm]\n\n{{The College of William & Mary}}\n{{coord |display=title|37.270471|-76.708255}}\n\n[[Category:School buildings completed in 1723]]\n[[Category:College of William & Mary buildings]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2010-13 \u2192 2010\u201313", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brafferton_(building)"}
{"title_page": "Shanghai American School", "text_new": "{{advert|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = Shanghai American School\n| logo = Shanghai American School (SAS).jpg\n| image = SAS Puxi Campus.jpg\n| caption = Puxi Campus\n| motto = Possumus Quia Posse Videmur\n| motto_translation = \"Since we think we can, we can.\"\n| location = Shanghai, China\n| former_name = American Private School (1941-42); Community Private School (1942-43); Chapei Civilian Assembly Camp school (1943-45); Shanghai American Private School (1945-46); Private American School (1949-50)\n| type = Independent, Pre-K-12\n| established = 1912\n| head_of_school = Marcel G. Gauthier\n| faculty = 388 from 51 countries\n| enrollment = 2,800 from 44 countries\n| campuses = Pudong (22 acres north of Pudong International Airport); Puxi (29 acres in Shanghai\u2019s Minhang district)\n| athletics = APAC (Asia Pacific Activities Conference), CISSA (China International Schools Sports)\n| nickname = Eagles\n| affiliations = Western Association of Schools and Colleges (WASC), College Board Advanced Placement, International Baccalarureate Diploma Programme, Principal Training Center\n| website = www.saschina.org\n| colors = Schoolwide\n{{Color box|#CC3333|border=darkgray}} [[Red]]\n{{Color box|#3366CC|border=darkgray}} [[Blue]]\n{{Color box|#FFFFFF|border=darkgray}} [[White]]\nPuxi {{Color box|#CC9933|border=darkgray}} [[Gold (color)|Gold]]\nPudong {{Color box|#CCCCCC|border=darkgray}} [[Silver (color)|Silver]]\n}}\n[[File:Aquatic Center .jpg|thumb|Aquatic Center, Puxi Campus]]'''Shanghai American School''' ('''SAS''') is an independent, not-for-profit international school located in [[Shanghai]], [[China]]. Founded in 1912, SAS has two campuses and over 2,800 students enrolled in Pre-K through 12th grade, making it China's largest international school.\n\nThe Puxi campus is located in [[Huacao Town]], [[Minhang District]],  and the Pudong campus is located in the Shanghai Links Executive Community in [[Pudong]].<ref>[http://www.saschina.org/ Home page]. Shanghai American School. Retrieved on February 19, 2014. \"Puxi Campus 258 Jinfeng Road Huacao Town, Minhang Dist. Shanghai, China 201107 6221-1445\" and \"Pudong Campus Shanghai Links Executive Community 1600 Lingbai Road Sanjiagang, Pudong Shanghai, China 201201 6221-1445\"</ref>\n[[File:SAS 1949 Cheerleaders.jpg|thumb|1949 SAS cheerleaders]]\n[[File:Books to Eat.jpg|thumb|Books to Eat, SAS Pudong Campus]]\n\n==Academics==\nThe school has various signature programs, including Innovation Institute,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/shanghaiamericanschool/docs/eagle_review_spring_2016/6|title=Opening of the CID|last=|first=|date=1 June 2016|website=ISSUU Eagle Review|access-date=12 December 2017}}</ref> a two-year interdisciplinary project based learning program, and Microcampus,<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.sasmicrocampus.org|title=Shanghai American School: Microcampus|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref>, a month-long immersion into a small village in China's Yunnan Province. Microcampus has been recognized by hundrED as one of the 100 most innovative education programs in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hundred.org/en/innovations/microcampus|title=Want students to see a village as their classroom?Microcampus|last=|first=|date=20 September 2017|website=hundrED|access-date=12 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nBoth campuses, in Puxi and Pudong,  offer [[Advanced Placement]] and [[International Baccalaureate Diploma's]], as well as both programmes together to high school students.\n\n==Activities==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2017}}\nStudents participate in over 150 clubs, sports, and other activities including National English Honor Society, [[National Honor Society]], [[Rho Kappa Honor Society]], [[Model United Nations]], [[International Thespian Society]], and [[Tri-M Music Honor Society]].\n\nSAS is a founding member of [[Asia Pacific Activities Conference]] (APAC), which comprises some of the largest international schools in [[Asia]]. Through APAC, SAS students participate in a variety of intramural recreations, including badminton, volleyball, band, choir, and theater. The school also co-founded the China Cup and Tri-Cities competitions. SAS students also participate in the [[China International Schools Sports Association]] (CISSA) League.\n\n==History==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2017}}\n\n'''Early Decades'''\n\nSAS opened on September 17, 1912 with 38 students and a two-building campus in Shanghai's Hongkou neighborhood, north of the Bund. The school was originally intended to serve \"the children of American missionaries and other European residents in the East\" but quickly established a reputation for academic excellence, and within a decade, the campus had grown to include twelve buildings on or near North Sichuan Road. With the support of the American business community in Shanghai and abroad, SAS broke ground on a purpose-built campus located amid farmland on the western edge of \"Frenchtown\" (today's former [[Shanghai French Concession|French Concession]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amcham-shanghai.org/our-history|title=Our History|last=|first=|date=13 December 2017|website=Shanghai American Chamber of Commerce|access-date=13 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1923, SAS moved to a new campus located on Avenue Petain (now [[Hengshan Road]]), whose administration building was modeled after Philadelphia's Independence Hall. (It can still be seen along Hengshan Road; the Girl's Dormitory and Water Tower also remain but are not visible from the road.)\n\nOver the next two decades, SAS's fortunes echoed those of its host city of Shanghai \u2013 from the prosperous days of the mid-\u201820s and \u201830s to the challenging times of war in 1927, 1932, and 1937.\n\nIn 1941, faced with a declining foreign population and with a world war growing in scope, the SAS Board of Managers made the decision to close the school.\n\n'''Bootleg SAS'''\n\nUpon hearing of the Board\u2019s decision, a SAS teacher named Frank \"Unk\" Cheney declared the school must go on. He gathered remaining faculty, staff, and equipment and continued SAS under a series of different names. He called them \"Bootleg SAS.\"\n\nBootleg SAS operated out of the SAS campus on Hengshan Road, as well as in the Community Church across the street (still an active church at 53 Hengshan Road). In 1943, Cheney and most of the SAS population were forced into [[Chapei Civilian Assembly Camp]], a Japanese-run internment camp. Still not content to see the school cease operations, Cheney packed thousands of books and brought them to internment camp so school could go on. Housed in an open-air shed with the most rudimentary supplies, the newest iteration of Bootleg SAS nevertheless opened with 222 students. At the end of World War II, the SAS Board of Managers vowed to re-open SAS in the fall of 1946. Unwilling to wait an additional year, Cheney opened yet another Bootleg SAS in the fall of 1945 to serve students until SAS could officially open the following fall.\n\n'''Post-WWII'''\n\nAt SAS, the period of 1946-49 saw the return of old traditions, sports and arts programs. The school and its campus were even featured in LIFE magazine. But by 1949, with China at the end of a civil war and Shanghai about to be invaded by the Communist Party, the SAS Board of Managers once again made the decision to close the school.\n\nWith Unk Cheney no longer on staff, a vice principal named Val Sundt was inspired to invoke the \"Spirit of Cheney\" and assure the school would once again continue.\n\nSundt founded the final Bootleg SAS in 1949\u201350, called Private American School. At the conclusion of the school year in May 1950, Sundt closed the school's doors, and the remaining SAS teachers and students heeded the warnings of the U.S. State Department and departed Shanghai.\n\n'''The Re-founding'''\n\nIn January 1980, encouraged by the reformist efforts of Chinese leader [[Deng Xiaoping]], the U.S. re-established its Consulate in Shanghai. One of the Consulate's first employees, economics advisor Tom Lauer, brought his wife, Linnea, and three children to Shanghai. Recognizing a need to educate the children of Consulate employees, the U.S. State Department asked Mrs. Lauer to restart Shanghai American School.\n\nSAS re-opened on the U.S. Consulate grounds on [[Huaihai Road|Huai Hai Road]] in September 1980. It remained there until outgrowing the space in 1989.\n\nThe Shanghai Girls #3 School, one of Shanghai's most reputable schools, with an alumni list that includes China's famous [[Soong sisters]],{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} agreed to share space with SAS. With a booming foreign population coming into Shanghai, a SAS education was in heavy demand and in spite of building additional buildings and floors, it wasn't long before SAS had again outgrown its space.\n\n'''Pit Stop Campus Era'''\n\nBy the mid-1990s, SAS had decided to build not one but two purpose-built campuses \u2013 one on each side of Shanghai's Huangpu River. Before the campus construction could be completed, the school needed to move once again.\n\nThree temporary campuses were established. In Puxi, a semi-built cultural center in Zhudi Town was reassigned to the school. In Pudong, another cultural center \u2013 Huaxia \u2013 was selected to be SAS\u2019 first presence on the Pudong side of the Huangpu River. A third temporary campus was founded in the Shanghai Centre on Nanjing Road to serve the youngest SAS attendees, though it soon proved unnecessary and closed after just one semester.\n\nFacilities during this time in SAS history were makeshift at best. The school's swim team held competitions at Shanghai's Holiday Inn, and storefronts across from campus served as classrooms. Ignoring the challenges of the times, the school laid plans for a brighter future. SAS became a co-founder of the region's Asia Pacific Athletic Conference (APAC), in spite of having no athletics facilities at the time.\n\n'''Modern-day SAS'''\n\nIn 1998, the Pudong campus opened on the shores of the East China Sea. In 2000, the Puxi campus opened in the heart of the Minhang district. \n\nIn 2017, James Mikkelson, a veteran English teacher at the Puxi campus, was fired after being found in possession of pornography on his school computer and exchanging explicit messages with former students. He was also the subject of numerous sexual misconduct allegations.<ref>https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s?__biz=MzA5NzEzNjEwNA%3D%3D&mid=2247488096&idx=2&sn=d1c795c99807d42da2b1702623e12184&chksm=90a42ee7a7d3a7f1a21ef39b283d3678db916a9e3a4f5dd7db1199c278c345c8f373a167675f#rd</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of international schools in Shanghai]]\n* [[Americans in China]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.saschina.org/ Shanghai American School website]\n* [http://gsgi.co.uk/countries/china/shanghai/shanghai-american-school-sas? Profile at the ''[[Good Schools Guide International]]'']\n* [https://archive.is/20130415184814/http://teachers.saschina.org/edpro/ Shanghai American School Educational Programs Blog]\n* [http://www.timeoutshanghai.com/venue/Family-International_Schools/75/Shanghai-American-School-(SAS),-Pudong.html?fromFamily=1 SAS Pudong's school profile on ''Time Out Shanghai Family'']\n* [http://www.timeoutshanghai.com/venue/Family-International_Schools/76/Shanghai-American-School-(SAS),-Puxi.html?fromFamily=1 SAS Puxi's school profile on ''Time Out Shanghai Family'']\n{{Pudong}}\n{{Minhang District}}\n{{International schools in Shanghai}}\n{{American schools in China}}\n{{coord missing|Shanghai}}\n\n[[Category:American international schools in China]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1912]]\n[[Category:International schools in Shanghai]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in China]]\n[[Category:Association of China and Mongolia International Schools]]\n[[Category:EARCOS]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:Schools in Pudong]]\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = Shanghai American School\n| logo = Shanghai American School (SAS).jpg\n| image = SAS Puxi Campus.jpg\n| caption = Puxi Campus\n| motto = Possumus Quia Posse Videmur\n| motto_translation = \"Since we think we can, we can.\"\n| location = Shanghai, China\n| former_name = American Private School (1941-42); Community Private School (1942-43); Chapei Civilian Assembly Camp school (1943-45); Shanghai American Private School (1945-46); Private American School (1949-50)\n| type = Independent, Pre-K-12\n| established = 1912\n| head_of_school = Marcel G. Gauthier\n| faculty = 388 from 51 countries\n| enrollment = 2,800 from 44 countries\n| campuses = Pudong (22 acres north of Pudong International Airport); Puxi (29 acres in Shanghai\u2019s Minhang district)\n| athletics = APAC (Asia Pacific Activities Conference), CISSA (China International Schools Sports)\n| nickname = Eagles\n| affiliations = Western Association of Schools and Colleges (WASC), College Board Advanced Placement, International Baccalarureate Diploma Programme, Principal Training Center\n| website = www.saschina.org\n| colors = Schoolwide\n{{Color box|#CC3333|border=darkgray}} [[Red]]\n{{Color box|#3366CC|border=darkgray}} [[Blue]]\n{{Color box|#FFFFFF|border=darkgray}} [[White]]\nPuxi {{Color box|#CC9933|border=darkgray}} [[Gold (color)|Gold]]\nPudong {{Color box|#CCCCCC|border=darkgray}} [[Silver (color)|Silver]]\n}}\n[[File:Aquatic Center .jpg|thumb|Aquatic Center, Puxi Campus]]'''Shanghai American School''' ('''SAS''') is an independent, not-for-profit international school located in [[Shanghai]], [[China]]. Founded in 1912, SAS has two campuses and over 2,800 students enrolled in Pre-K through 12th grade, making it China's largest international school.\n\nThe Puxi campus is located in [[Huacao Town]], [[Minhang District]],  and the Pudong campus is located in the Shanghai Links Executive Community in [[Pudong]].<ref>[http://www.saschina.org/ Home page]. Shanghai American School. Retrieved on February 19, 2014. \"Puxi Campus 258 Jinfeng Road Huacao Town, Minhang Dist. Shanghai, China 201107 6221-1445\" and \"Pudong Campus Shanghai Links Executive Community 1600 Lingbai Road Sanjiagang, Pudong Shanghai, China 201201 6221-1445\"</ref>\n[[File:SAS 1949 Cheerleaders.jpg|thumb|1949 SAS cheerleaders]]\n[[File:Books to Eat.jpg|thumb|Books to Eat, SAS Pudong Campus]]\n\n==Academics==\nThe school has various signature programs, including Innovation Institute,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/shanghaiamericanschool/docs/eagle_review_spring_2016/6|title=Opening of the CID|last=|first=|date=1 June 2016|website=ISSUU Eagle Review|access-date=12 December 2017}}</ref> a two-year interdisciplinary project based learning program, and Microcampus,<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.sasmicrocampus.org|title=Shanghai American School: Microcampus|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref>, a month-long immersion into a small village in China's Yunnan Province. Microcampus has been recognized by hundrED as one of the 100 most innovative education programs in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hundred.org/en/innovations/microcampus|title=Want students to see a village as their classroom?Microcampus|last=|first=|date=20 September 2017|website=hundrED|access-date=12 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nBoth campuses, in Puxi and Pudong,  offer [[Advanced Placement]] and [[International Baccalaureate Diploma's]], as well as both programmes together to high school students.\n\n==Activities==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2017}}\nStudents participate in over 150 clubs, sports, and other activities including National English Honor Society, [[National Honor Society]], [[Rho Kappa Honor Society]], [[Model United Nations]], [[International Thespian Society]], and [[Tri-M Music Honor Society]].\n\nSAS is a founding member of [[Asia Pacific Activities Conference]] (APAC), which comprises some of the largest international schools in [[Asia]]. Through APAC, SAS students participate in a variety of intramural recreations, including badminton, volleyball, band, choir, and theater. The school also co-founded the China Cup and Tri-Cities competitions. SAS students also participate in the [[China International Schools Sports Association]] (CISSA) League.\n\n==History==\n{{unreferenced section|date=December 2017}}\n\n'''Early Decades'''\n\nSAS opened on September 17, 1912 with 38 students and a two-building campus in Shanghai's Hongkou neighborhood, north of the Bund. The school was originally intended to serve \"the children of American missionaries and other European residents in the East\" but quickly established a reputation for academic excellence, and within a decade, the campus had grown to include twelve buildings on or near North Sichuan Road. With the support of the American business community in Shanghai and abroad, SAS broke ground on a purpose-built campus located amid farmland on the western edge of \"Frenchtown\" (today's former [[Shanghai French Concession|French Concession]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amcham-shanghai.org/our-history|title=Our History|last=|first=|date=13 December 2017|website=Shanghai American Chamber of Commerce|access-date=13 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1923, SAS moved to a new campus located on Avenue Petain (now [[Hengshan Road]]), whose administration building was modeled after Philadelphia's Independence Hall. (It can still be seen along Hengshan Road; the Girl's Dormitory and Water Tower also remain but are not visible from the road.)\n\nOver the next two decades, SAS's fortunes echoed those of its host city of Shanghai \u2013 from the prosperous days of the mid-\u201820s and \u201830s to the challenging times of war in 1927, 1932, and 1937.\n\nIn 1941, faced with a declining foreign population and with a world war growing in scope, the SAS Board of Managers made the decision to close the school.\n\n'''Bootleg SAS'''\n\nUpon hearing of the Board\u2019s decision, a SAS teacher named Frank \"Unk\" Cheney declared the school must go on. He gathered remaining faculty, staff, and equipment and continued SAS under a series of different names. He called them \"Bootleg SAS.\"\n\nBootleg SAS operated out of the SAS campus on Hengshan Road, as well as in the Community Church across the street (still an active church at 53 Hengshan Road). In 1943, Cheney and most of the SAS population were forced into [[Chapei Civilian Assembly Camp]], a Japanese-run internment camp. Still not content to see the school cease operations, Cheney packed thousands of books and brought them to internment camp so school could go on. Housed in an open-air shed with the most rudimentary supplies, the newest iteration of Bootleg SAS nevertheless opened with 222 students. At the end of World War II, the SAS Board of Managers vowed to re-open SAS in the fall of 1946. Unwilling to wait an additional year, Cheney opened yet another Bootleg SAS in the fall of 1945 to serve students until SAS could officially open the following fall.\n\n'''Post-WWII'''\n\nAt SAS, the period of 1946-49 saw the return of old traditions, sports and arts programs. The school and its campus were even featured in LIFE magazine. But by 1949, with China at the end of a civil war and Shanghai about to be invaded by the Communist Party, the SAS Board of Managers once again made the decision to close the school.\n\nWith Unk Cheney no longer on staff, a vice principal named Val Sundt was inspired to invoke the \"Spirit of Cheney\" and assure the school would once again continue.\n\nSundt founded the final Bootleg SAS in 1949-50, called Private American School. At the conclusion of the school year in May 1950, Sundt closed the school's doors, and the remaining SAS teachers and students heeded the warnings of the U.S. State Department and departed Shanghai.\n\n'''The Re-founding'''\n\nIn January 1980, encouraged by the reformist efforts of Chinese leader [[Deng Xiaoping]], the U.S. re-established its Consulate in Shanghai. One of the Consulate's first employees, economics advisor Tom Lauer, brought his wife, Linnea, and three children to Shanghai. Recognizing a need to educate the children of Consulate employees, the U.S. State Department asked Mrs. Lauer to restart Shanghai American School.\n\nSAS re-opened on the U.S. Consulate grounds on [[Huaihai Road|Huai Hai Road]] in September 1980. It remained there until outgrowing the space in 1989.\n\nThe Shanghai Girls #3 School, one of Shanghai's most reputable schools, with an alumni list that includes China's famous [[Soong sisters]],{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} agreed to share space with SAS. With a booming foreign population coming into Shanghai, a SAS education was in heavy demand and in spite of building additional buildings and floors, it wasn't long before SAS had again outgrown its space.\n\n'''Pit Stop Campus Era'''\n\nBy the mid-1990s, SAS had decided to build not one but two purpose-built campuses \u2013 one on each side of Shanghai's Huangpu River. Before the campus construction could be completed, the school needed to move once again.\n\nThree temporary campuses were established. In Puxi, a semi-built cultural center in Zhudi Town was reassigned to the school. In Pudong, another cultural center \u2013 Huaxia \u2013 was selected to be SAS\u2019 first presence on the Pudong side of the Huangpu River. A third temporary campus was founded in the Shanghai Centre on Nanjing Road to serve the youngest SAS attendees, though it soon proved unnecessary and closed after just one semester.\n\nFacilities during this time in SAS history were makeshift at best. The school's swim team held competitions at Shanghai's Holiday Inn, and storefronts across from campus served as classrooms. Ignoring the challenges of the times, the school laid plans for a brighter future. SAS became a co-founder of the region's Asia Pacific Athletic Conference (APAC), in spite of having no athletics facilities at the time.\n\n'''Modern-day SAS'''\n\nIn 1998, the Pudong campus opened on the shores of the East China Sea. In 2000, the Puxi campus opened in the heart of the Minhang district. \n\nIn 2017, James Mikkelson, a veteran English teacher at the Puxi campus, was fired after being found in possession of pornography on his school computer and exchanging explicit messages with former students. He was also the subject of numerous sexual misconduct allegations.<ref>https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s?__biz=MzA5NzEzNjEwNA%3D%3D&mid=2247488096&idx=2&sn=d1c795c99807d42da2b1702623e12184&chksm=90a42ee7a7d3a7f1a21ef39b283d3678db916a9e3a4f5dd7db1199c278c345c8f373a167675f#rd</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of international schools in Shanghai]]\n* [[Americans in China]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.saschina.org/ Shanghai American School website]\n* [http://gsgi.co.uk/countries/china/shanghai/shanghai-american-school-sas? Profile at the ''[[Good Schools Guide International]]'']\n* [https://archive.is/20130415184814/http://teachers.saschina.org/edpro/ Shanghai American School Educational Programs Blog]\n* [http://www.timeoutshanghai.com/venue/Family-International_Schools/75/Shanghai-American-School-(SAS),-Pudong.html?fromFamily=1 SAS Pudong's school profile on ''Time Out Shanghai Family'']\n* [http://www.timeoutshanghai.com/venue/Family-International_Schools/76/Shanghai-American-School-(SAS),-Puxi.html?fromFamily=1 SAS Puxi's school profile on ''Time Out Shanghai Family'']\n{{Pudong}}\n{{Minhang District}}\n{{International schools in Shanghai}}\n{{American schools in China}}\n{{coord missing|Shanghai}}\n\n[[Category:American international schools in China]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1912]]\n[[Category:International schools in Shanghai]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in China]]\n[[Category:Association of China and Mongolia International Schools]]\n[[Category:EARCOS]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:Schools in Pudong]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1949-50 \u2192 1949\u201350", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shanghai_American_School"}
{"title_page": "KCSB-FM", "text_new": "{{Infobox radio station \n|name = KCSB-FM\n|image = Kcsb.jpg\n|image_size = 180px\n|area = [[Santa Barbara, California]]\n|branding = ''Independent''\n|slogan = \n|airdate = [[1962 in radio|1962]]\n|frequency = 91.9 ([[Megahertz|MHz]])\n|format = [[Non-commercial educational|Non-commercial]]/[[Eclecticism in music|Eclectic]]\n|erp = 620 [[watt]]s\n|haat = {{convert|879|m|ft|0|abbr=off}}\n|class = B\n|facility_id = 69081\n|coordinates = {{Coord|34.525278|N|119.958056|W|format=dms}}\n|callsign_meaning = Community Service Broadcasting (derived from UCSB)\n|owner = [[Students' Association|Associated Students]] of [[University of California, Santa Barbara|UCSB]]\n|webcast = [http://www.kcsb-radio.dreamhosters.com/webcast/ Listen Live]\n|website = [http://www.kcsb.org/ kcsb.org]\n}}\n'''KCSB-FM''' (91.9 [[FM broadcasting|FM]]) is a non-commercial, educational [[radio station]] located on the [[University of California, Santa Barbara|UC Santa Barbara]] campus.\nKCSB is designed to be educational for both programmers and listeners. UCSB students and other programmers are provided an opportunity to learn the fundamentals of radio broadcasting, both technically and in terms of broadcast content, and to explore more advanced aspects of broadcasting and the audio medium. The station has a range that reaches as far south as [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]] and as far north as [[San Luis Obispo, California]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Durnhofer |first=Nick |title=Dish Failure Hurts KCSB Pledge Drive |publisher=UC Santa Barbara Daily Nexus |url=http://www.dailynexus.com/article.php?a=8368 |date=November 12, 2004 |accessdate=January 30, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070105000853/http://www.dailynexus.com/article.php?a=8368 |archivedate=January 5, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nKCSB was started by student Bill Harrison<ref>{{cite web|last=Coe|first=Ted|title=KCSB Founder Bill Harrison Interviewed on \"Real Gauchos\"|url=http://www.kcsb.org/interviews/kcsb-founder-bill-harrison-interviewed|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130415061539/http://www.kcsb.org/interviews/kcsb-founder-bill-harrison-interviewed|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 April 2013|publisher=KCSB|accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref>  as ''Navajo Radio,'' named for Navajo Hall,<ref>{{cite web|last=Marshall|first=Colin|title=This Is KCSB|url=http://www.independent.com/news/2010/nov/11/kcsb/|publisher=The Santa Barbara Independent|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> a 2nd floor wing in the Anacapa men's dormitory from which it began broadcasting in 1962, broadcasting 3 &ndash; 4 hours of daily programming to the UCSB dorms at 5 watts. It was the first [[University of California]] station to be licensed. It gradually grew into the station it is today, changing frequency in 1976 and undergoing wattage expansions in 1964 and 1983. On April 18, 1970, KCSB was shut down by the [[Santa Barbara County Sheriff's Office]]. The department took the measure as a precaution against rioting, which they felt would occur if the UCSB and [[Isla Vista]] community became aware of the events of the [[Isla Vista#1960s and 1970s|Isla Vista riots]], an outgrowth of anger originating with the [[Vietnam War]] that was ignited by the firing of a popular professor. The incident is the only one on record of a police force shutting down a radio station. In 1989, the station was embroiled in a controversy revolving around the dismissal of volunteer host [[Sean Hannity]] for featuring a guest who made offensive remarks about homosexuals.<ref>{{cite web|last=Palladino|first=D.J.|title=KCSB Celebrates 50 Years on the Air|url=http://www.independent.com/news/2012/apr/25/kcsb-celebrates-50-years-air/|publisher=The Santa Barbara Independent|accessdate=18 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012051406/http://www.independent.com/news/2012/apr/25/kcsb-celebrates-50-years-air/|archive-date=12 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The Santa Barbara chapter of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] defended Hannity's right to [[Freedom of speech|free speech]], and the station offered Hannity his slot back. He did not accept the offer, instead demanding more airtime.\n\nKCSB celebrated its 50th anniversary in 2012.  The year-long celebration included a design contest, a nostalgic addition to the KCSB program which aired archived shows, an alumni reunion, an audio exhibit and a radio-themed film series.\n\n==Programming==\nThe KCSB schedule of programming is pre-prepared each quarter by the PMRC (Program Mediation and Review Committee). New DJs are required to submit a demo tape, demonstrating an ability to provide alternative programming and a certain amount of skill using the mixing board. Slots are assigned according to programmer availability, quality of programming, and seniority. Before applying to KCSB, interested DJs must complete a quarter of training on KJUC (the AM training station that can only be heard in the dorms), and receive a passing score on the [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]] test. Any member of the community may try for a spot on the schedule. Besides offering unique musical programming, KCSB is a conduit of community news and information, including UCSB athletics, and features the popular national news program [[Democracy Now]]. The station has been [[webcasting]] since the 1990s.\n\nAfter 31 years employed at UCSB, KCSB Advisor Elizabeth Robinson retired at the end of Spring Quarter 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stefani|first=Katelyn|title=KCSB Director Elizabeth Robinson Retires|url=http://thebottomline.as.ucsb.edu/2012/05/kcsb-director-elizabeth-robinson-retires|publisher=The Bottom Line|accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref> An executive committee made up of UCSB students administer various aspects of the station including promotions, publications, programming and engineering.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcsb.org/contact/|title=KCSB|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Notable personalities==\nThe following notable individuals have been featured by KCSB as on-air personalities:\n* [[Sean Hannity]], talk radio host and the host of Fox News Channel's program ''Hannity''. Was on KCSB during the late 1980s.\n* [[Edie Lambert]], News anchor @ [[KCRA-TV]] in Sacramento, formerly @ [[KEYT-TV]]-3 in Santa Barbara. Edie was in the News Department at KCSB in the late 1980s.\n* [[Jeffrey Peterson]], famous technology entrepreneur. Was a DJ and Traffic Manager at KCSB from 1986\u20131990.\n* [[Jim Rome]], sports radio host syndicated by Clear Channel. Worked at KCSB during the mid-1980s and was Sports Director for one quarter. Was also sports director at [[KTMS]]-AM 1250 in Santa Barbara for two years after graduating from UCSB.\n* [[Zan Stewart]], award-winning jazz journalist, on air in 1964 and again 1972\u20131974.\n* [[Mike Sugerman]], Emmy award-winning reporter for [[KPIX]]-TV, CBS-5, San Francisco, and [[KCBS (AM)|KCBS]] Radio in San Francisco, anchored news on KCSB-FM in the early 1970s. He also had a music program under the air name of \"The Golden Beaver\".\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of community radio stations in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.kcsb.org/ KCSB official website]\n*[http://www.facebook.com/pages/KCSB-FM-919-in-Santa-Barbara/121864956626 KCSB on Facebook]\n{{FM station data|KCSB}}\n\n{{Santa Barbara Radio}}\n{{California college radio}}\n{{UCSB}}\n\n{{Coord|34|24|46|N|119|50|53|W|format=dms|display=title|type:landmark_region:US-CA}}\n\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Barbara]]\n[[Category:College radio stations in California|CSB-FM]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in California|CSB-FM]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1962]]\n[[Category:Community radio stations in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox radio station \n|name = KCSB-FM\n|image = Kcsb.jpg\n|image_size = 180px\n|area = [[Santa Barbara, California]]\n|branding = ''Independent''\n|slogan = \n|airdate = [[1962 in radio|1962]]\n|frequency = 91.9 ([[Megahertz|MHz]])\n|format = [[Non-commercial educational|Non-commercial]]/[[Eclecticism in music|Eclectic]]\n|erp = 620 [[watt]]s\n|haat = {{convert|879|m|ft|0|abbr=off}}\n|class = B\n|facility_id = 69081\n|coordinates = {{Coord|34.525278|N|119.958056|W|format=dms}}\n|callsign_meaning = Community Service Broadcasting (derived from UCSB)\n|owner = [[Students' Association|Associated Students]] of [[University of California, Santa Barbara|UCSB]]\n|webcast = [http://www.kcsb-radio.dreamhosters.com/webcast/ Listen Live]\n|website = [http://www.kcsb.org/ kcsb.org]\n}}\n'''KCSB-FM''' (91.9 [[FM broadcasting|FM]]) is a non-commercial, educational [[radio station]] located on the [[University of California, Santa Barbara|UC Santa Barbara]] campus.\nKCSB is designed to be educational for both programmers and listeners. UCSB students and other programmers are provided an opportunity to learn the fundamentals of radio broadcasting, both technically and in terms of broadcast content, and to explore more advanced aspects of broadcasting and the audio medium. The station has a range that reaches as far south as [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]] and as far north as [[San Luis Obispo, California]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Durnhofer |first=Nick |title=Dish Failure Hurts KCSB Pledge Drive |publisher=UC Santa Barbara Daily Nexus |url=http://www.dailynexus.com/article.php?a=8368 |date=November 12, 2004 |accessdate=January 30, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070105000853/http://www.dailynexus.com/article.php?a=8368 |archivedate=January 5, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nKCSB was started by student Bill Harrison<ref>{{cite web|last=Coe|first=Ted|title=KCSB Founder Bill Harrison Interviewed on \"Real Gauchos\"|url=http://www.kcsb.org/interviews/kcsb-founder-bill-harrison-interviewed|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130415061539/http://www.kcsb.org/interviews/kcsb-founder-bill-harrison-interviewed|url-status=dead|archive-date=15 April 2013|publisher=KCSB|accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref>  as ''Navajo Radio,'' named for Navajo Hall,<ref>{{cite web|last=Marshall|first=Colin|title=This Is KCSB|url=http://www.independent.com/news/2010/nov/11/kcsb/|publisher=The Santa Barbara Independent|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> a 2nd floor wing in the Anacapa men's dormitory from which it began broadcasting in 1962, broadcasting 3 &ndash; 4 hours of daily programming to the UCSB dorms at 5 watts. It was the first [[University of California]] station to be licensed. It gradually grew into the station it is today, changing frequency in 1976 and undergoing wattage expansions in 1964 and 1983. On April 18, 1970, KCSB was shut down by the [[Santa Barbara County Sheriff's Office]]. The department took the measure as a precaution against rioting, which they felt would occur if the UCSB and [[Isla Vista]] community became aware of the events of the [[Isla Vista#1960s and 1970s|Isla Vista riots]], an outgrowth of anger originating with the [[Vietnam War]] that was ignited by the firing of a popular professor. The incident is the only one on record of a police force shutting down a radio station. In 1989, the station was embroiled in a controversy revolving around the dismissal of volunteer host [[Sean Hannity]] for featuring a guest who made offensive remarks about homosexuals.<ref>{{cite web|last=Palladino|first=D.J.|title=KCSB Celebrates 50 Years on the Air|url=http://www.independent.com/news/2012/apr/25/kcsb-celebrates-50-years-air/|publisher=The Santa Barbara Independent|accessdate=18 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012051406/http://www.independent.com/news/2012/apr/25/kcsb-celebrates-50-years-air/|archive-date=12 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The Santa Barbara chapter of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] defended Hannity's right to [[Freedom of speech|free speech]], and the station offered Hannity his slot back. He did not accept the offer, instead demanding more airtime.\n\nKCSB celebrated its 50th anniversary in 2012.  The year-long celebration included a design contest, a nostalgic addition to the KCSB program which aired archived shows, an alumni reunion, an audio exhibit and a radio-themed film series.\n\n==Programming==\nThe KCSB schedule of programming is pre-prepared each quarter by the PMRC (Program Mediation and Review Committee). New DJs are required to submit a demo tape, demonstrating an ability to provide alternative programming and a certain amount of skill using the mixing board. Slots are assigned according to programmer availability, quality of programming, and seniority. Before applying to KCSB, interested DJs must complete a quarter of training on KJUC (the AM training station that can only be heard in the dorms), and receive a passing score on the [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]] test. Any member of the community may try for a spot on the schedule. Besides offering unique musical programming, KCSB is a conduit of community news and information, including UCSB athletics, and features the popular national news program [[Democracy Now]]. The station has been [[webcasting]] since the 1990s.\n\nAfter 31 years employed at UCSB, KCSB Advisor Elizabeth Robinson retired at the end of Spring Quarter 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stefani|first=Katelyn|title=KCSB Director Elizabeth Robinson Retires|url=http://thebottomline.as.ucsb.edu/2012/05/kcsb-director-elizabeth-robinson-retires|publisher=The Bottom Line|accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref> An executive committee made up of UCSB students administer various aspects of the station including promotions, publications, programming and engineering.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcsb.org/contact/|title=KCSB|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Notable personalities==\nThe following notable individuals have been featured by KCSB as on-air personalities:\n* [[Sean Hannity]], talk radio host and the host of Fox News Channel's program ''Hannity''. Was on KCSB during the late 1980s.\n* [[Edie Lambert]], News anchor @ [[KCRA-TV]] in Sacramento, formerly @ [[KEYT-TV]]-3 in Santa Barbara. Edie was in the News Department at KCSB in the late 1980s.\n* [[Jeffrey Peterson]], famous technology entrepreneur. Was a DJ and Traffic Manager at KCSB from 1986-1990.\n* [[Jim Rome]], sports radio host syndicated by Clear Channel. Worked at KCSB during the mid-1980s and was Sports Director for one quarter. Was also sports director at [[KTMS]]-AM 1250 in Santa Barbara for two years after graduating from UCSB.\n* [[Zan Stewart]], award-winning jazz journalist, on air in 1964 and again 1972-1974.\n* [[Mike Sugerman]], Emmy award-winning reporter for [[KPIX]]-TV, CBS-5, San Francisco, and [[KCBS (AM)|KCBS]] Radio in San Francisco, anchored news on KCSB-FM in the early 1970s. He also had a music program under the air name of \"The Golden Beaver\".\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of community radio stations in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.kcsb.org/ KCSB official website]\n*[http://www.facebook.com/pages/KCSB-FM-919-in-Santa-Barbara/121864956626 KCSB on Facebook]\n{{FM station data|KCSB}}\n\n{{Santa Barbara Radio}}\n{{California college radio}}\n{{UCSB}}\n\n{{Coord|34|24|46|N|119|50|53|W|format=dms|display=title|type:landmark_region:US-CA}}\n\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Barbara]]\n[[Category:College radio stations in California|CSB-FM]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in California|CSB-FM]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1962]]\n[[Category:Community radio stations in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable personalities:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1986-1990 \u2192 1986\u20131990 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KCSB-FM"}
{"title_page": "Big Game (American football)", "text_new": "{{Infobox sports rivalry\n| wide                  = yes\n| name                  = Big Game\n| image                 = \n| image_size            = \n| caption               = \n| team1                 = [[California Golden Bears football|California Golden Bears]]\n| team1logo             = California Golden Bears logo.svg\n| team3                 = [[Stanford Cardinal football|Stanford Cardinal]]\n| team3logo             = Stanford Cardinal logo.svg\n| sport                 = \n| firstmeeting          = March 19, 1892<br />Stanford 14, California 10\n| mostrecent            = November 23, 2019<br />California 24, Stanford 20\n| nextmeeting           = November 21, 2020\n| total                 = 122\n| series                =  Stanford leads, 59\u201344\u201310 ({{winning percentage|59|44|10}})<ref name=\"series\" />\n| largestvictory        = Stanford, 63\u201313 (2013)\n| longeststreak         = Stanford, 9 (2010\u20132018)\n| longestunbeatenstreak = \n| currentstreak         = California, 1 (2019\u2013present)\n| currentunbeatenstreak = \n| trophy                = [[Stanford Axe]]\n| trophy series         = \n| stadiums              =  \n| map_location          = \n| map_width             = \n| map_label1            = \n| map_mark1             = \n| map_label1_position   = \n| coordinates1          = \n| map_label2            = \n| map_mark2             = \n| map_label2_position   = \n| coordinates2          = \n| map_caption           = \n}}\n{{OSM Location map        \n| coord = {{coord|37.654444|-122.199833}}\n| zoom = 9\n| width = 295 \n| height = 250\n| caption = Locations of Cal and Stanford\n| mark1 = Red pog.svg\n| label1 = Stanford\n| mark-coord1 = {{coord|37.434444|-122.161111}}\n| label-pos1 = bottom\n| label-color1 = black\n| mark2 = Blue pog.svg\n| label2 = Cal\n| mark-coord2 = {{coord|37.871111|-122.250833}}\n| label-pos2 = top\n| label-color2 = black\n}}\n'''Big Game''' is the name given to the '''California\u2013Stanford football rivalry'''.<ref>https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/11/18/cal-makes-stanford-work-for-it-but-falls-in-120th-big-game/</ref><ref>https://www.ruleoftree.com/2017/11/14/16652110/history-big-game-stanford-cal</ref> It is an American [[college football]] [[college rivalry|rivalry]] game played by the [[California Golden Bears football]] team of the [[University of California, Berkeley]] and the [[Stanford Cardinal football]] team of [[Stanford University]]. Both institutions are located in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]]. First played in 1892, it is one of the oldest college rivalries in the United States. The game is typically played in late November or early December, and its location alternates between the two universities every year. In even-numbered years, the game is played at Berkeley, while in odd-numbered years it is played at Stanford.\n\n==Series history==\n{{multiple image\n| align    = left\n| footer   = Cal and Stanford teams that played the first Big Game in 1892\n| width    = \n| image1   = California football team 1892.jpg\n| width1   = 175\n| alt1     = \n| image2   = Stanford football team 1892.jpg\n| width2   = 155\n| alt2     = \n}}\n\nBig Game is the oldest college football rivalry in the West.\n\nWhile an undergraduate at Stanford, future U.S. President [[Herbert Hoover]] was the student manager of both the baseball and football teams.  He helped organize the inaugural Big Game, along with his friend Cal manager Herbert Lang.<ref name=\"origin\">{{Cite book|title=Big Games: College Football's Greatest Rivalries|last=Bradley|first=Michael|publisher=Potomac Books|year=2006|isbn=1574889087|location=|pages=221-222}}</ref>  Only 10,000 tickets were printed for the game but 20,000 people showed up. Hoover and Lang scrambled to find pots, bowls and any other available receptacles to collect the admission fees.<ref name=\"origin\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hamilton |first1=David E. |title=Herbert Hoover: Life Before the Presidency |url=https://millercenter.org/president/hoover/life-before-the-presidency |website=Miller Center |accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy 1900 the match was already referred to as the \"Big Game.\"<ref name=\"Ingrassia\" /> In 1898, Berkeley alumnus and San Francisco Mayor [[James D. Phelan]] purchased a casting of [[Douglas Tilden]]'s ''The Football Players'' bronze sculpture and offered it as a prize to the school that could win the football game two years in a row. Berkeley responded by shutting Stanford out in 1898 and 1899, and the sculpture was installed on the Berkeley campus atop a stone pedestal engraved with the names of the players and the donor during a dedication ceremony held May 12, 1900.<ref name=BDP-000806>{{cite news |url=http://www.berkeleydailyplanet.com/issue/2010-08-03/article/36028 |title=Famed Deaf Sculptor Died 75 Years Ago in Berkeley |author=Finacom, Steven |date=6 August 2010 |newspaper=The Berkeley Daily Planet |accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=GayBears>{{cite web |url=http://bancroft.berkeley.edu/collections/gaybears/tilden/ |title=Douglas Tilden 1860-1935 |author= |date=2002 |publisher=Bancroft Library, University of California at Berkeley |website=Gay Bears! The Hidden History of the Berkeley Campus |accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Big game 1905.jpg|thumb|right|The 1905 Big Game played at Stanford]]\nDuring the 1900 Big Game, played at the [[Recreation Park (San Francisco)|Recreation Park stadium]] on Thanksgiving Day in San Francisco, a large group of fans were observing from the roof of the nearby S.F. and Pacific Glass Works factory. With somewhere between 600 and 1,000 spectators atop it, the rooftop collapsed, resulting in well over 100 men falling to the factory's floor and more than 60 directly onto the massive, blazing furnace. In total 22 men, mostly boys, were killed, and more than 100 severely injured.<ref>Twenty Score Persons Make Awful Plunge: Seventeen People Meet Most Awful Death: Two San Jose Men Die Amid Sizzling Shrieking Human Mass in Collapsed Factory at Big Game, ''The (San Jose) Evening News'', (Friday 30 November 1900), [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GEoiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=B6QFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1470%2C5329715 p.1], [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GEoiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=B6QFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2068%2C5348447 p.5.]</ref><ref>[http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SFC19001130 Death Reaps a Dread Harvest of Lives and Plunges City into Gloom, ''The San Francisco Call'', (Friday, 30 November 1900), p.2.]</ref> To this day, the Thanksgiving Day Disaster remains the deadliest accident to kill spectators at a U.S. sporting event.<ref>[http://www.sfweekly.com/2012-08-15/news/football-san-francisco-and-pacific-glass-works-history-sports-tragedy/full Eskanazi, J., \"Sudden Death: Boys Fell to Their Doom in S.F.'s Forgotten Disaster\", ''San Francisco Weekly News'', 15 August 2012.]</ref>\n\nIn 1906, citing concerns about the violence in football, both schools dropped football in favor of [[Rugby union|Rugby]], which was played for the Big Games of 1906\u201314.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CAgyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=SuMFAAAAIBAJ&pg=748,3024990 |title=Many changes in rugby game |work=[[San Jose Mercury News|The Evening News (San Jose)]]|date=September 14, 1906|accessdate=November 10, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Stanford University \u2013 The First Twenty Five Years 1891\u20131925|last=Elliott|first=Orrin Leslie |pages=231\u2013233|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gpo2CdSpXLQC&pg=PA231|publisher=Stanford University Press|year=1937|location=Stanford, California|accessdate=November 10, 2010|isbn=9781406771411}}</ref> During that time the matches were played under Union rules of rugby per an agreement between Stanford and Cal coaches along with other West coast teams, including [[University of Nevada, Reno|Nevada]], [[Saint Mary's College of California|St. Mary's]], [[Santa Clara University|Santa Clara]], and [[University of Southern California|USC]] (in 1911)<ref name=Ingrassia>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-RWWDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA43 |title=San Francisco Bay Area Sports: Golden Gate Athletics, Recreation, and Community |author=Ingrassia, Brian M. |editor1=Liberti, Rita |editor2=Smith, Maureen |date=2017 |publisher=University of Arkansas Press |location=Fayetteville, Arkansas |isbn=978-1-61075-603-7 |chapter=3. Reforming the Big Game: the Bay Area Rugby Experiment of 1906\u20131919 |accessdate=19 October 2017 |pages=43\u201358}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal\n |url=http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/JSH/JSH1984/JSH1103/jsh1103b.pdf\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100807203402/http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/JSH/JSH1984/JSH1103/jsh1103b.pdf\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=2010-08-07\n |title=From Football to Rugby\u2014and Back, 1906\u20131919: The University of California\u2013Stanford University Response to the \"Football Crisis of 1905\" \n |last=Park \n |first=Roberta J \n |journal=Journal of Sport History \n |volume=11 \n |number=3 \n |page=33 \n |date=Winter 1984 \n}}</ref> In 1915, Cal switched back to American football.<ref name=\"Ingrassia\" /><ref name=\":0\" />  Its official reason for withdrawal from its 1915 rugby match against Stanford was the disagreement over Stanford's play of freshmen on their varsity team, however it was apparent that Cal intended to withdraw from the agreement to play rugby and instead play football against western schools that continued playing football or switched back several years earlier.<ref name=\":0\" /> Cal's Big Game was played in the years 1915\u201317, against [[Washington Huskies football|Washington]], games which aren't listed in Big Game records. Cal lost its 1915, home Big Game to University of Washington 72\u20130, while Stanford played rugby against its new Big Game opponent [[Santa Clara Broncos football|Santa Clara University]], beating them 30\u20130. Stanford played rugby for two more years.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nThe 1918 game, in which Cal prevailed 67\u20130, is not considered an official game because Stanford's football team was composed of volunteers from the [[ROTC|Student Army Training Corps]] stationed at Stanford, some of whom were not Stanford students.<ref name=\"migdol\" />{{rp | 58}} In 1919, Stanford officially switched back to playing football.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe first incidence of [[card stunts]] was performed by Cal fans at the halftime of the 1910 Big Game.<ref name=\"migdol\">{{cite book|last=Migdol|first=Gary|title=Stanford: Home of Champions\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ntBDmB_fYo8C|publisher=Sports Publishing LLC|year=1997|location=Champaign, Illinois|isbn=1-57167-116-1}}</ref>{{rp | 34\u201360}}\n\n[[File:Mud game 1912.jpg|thumb|left|From 1906 to 1914, the Big Game was played under the [[Laws of rugby union|rules of rugby union]]. The 1912 edition would be nicknamed ''the mud game'']]\nCalifornia resumed playing football in 1915, but [[1906\u201317 Stanford rugby teams|Stanford's rugby teams]] continued until 1917. From 1915 to 1917, California's \"Big Game\" was their game against [[Washington Huskies football|Washington]], while Stanford played [[Santa Clara Broncos|Santa Clara]] as their rugby \"Big Game\".<ref name=park>{{cite journal|url=http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/JSH/JSH1984/JSH1103/jsh1103b.pdf|title=From Football to Rugby\u2014and Back, 1906\u20131919: The University of California\u2013Stanford University Response to the \"Football Crisis of 1905\"|last=Park|first=Roberta J|journal=Journal of Sport History|volume=11|number=3|page=33|date=Winter 1984|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100807203402/http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/JSH/JSH1984/JSH1103/jsh1103b.pdf|archivedate=2010-08-07}}</ref> The game resumed as football in 1919, and has been played as such every year since, except from 1943 to 1945, when Stanford shut down its football program due to World War II. A handful of Stanford starters\u2014including guards [[Jim Cox (American football)|Jim Cox]], [[Bill Hachten]] and [[Fred Boensch]], running back George Quist and halfback Billy Agnew\u2014shifted to Cal in order to continue playing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gostanford.com/genrel/111705aab.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130102232920/http://www.gostanford.com/genrel/111705aab.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 2, 2013 |title=Bob Murphy Shares His Love of the Tradition of The Big Game: Murphy has been broadcasting Stanford football for over 40 years |date=November 17, 2005 |work=Cardinal Athletics |publisher=Stanford University |accessdate=December 29, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Alumni Gazette |last=Snapp |first=Martin |work=California |publisher=Cal Alumni Association |date=Winter 2011 |page=72 |volume=122 |number=4 |issn=0008-1302}}</ref> Quist returned to Stanford, playing against Cal in the 1946 Big Game.\n\nScenes for the [[Harold Lloyd]] silent classic ''[[The Freshman (1925 film)|The Freshman]]'' were filmed at [[California Memorial Stadium]] during halftime of the 1924 Big Game.\n\nSince 1933, the victor of the game has been awarded possession of the [[Stanford Axe]]. If a game ended in a tie, the Axe stayed on the side that already possessed it; this rule became obsolete in 1996 when the NCAA instituted overtime. The Axe is a key part of the rivalry's history, having been stolen on several occasions by both sides, starting in 1899, when the Axe was introduced when Stanford yell leader Billy Erb used it at a baseball game between the two schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stanford.edu/group/axecomm/axebook/origin2.html|title=The Stanford Axe- Origin and Loss of the Axe|author=|date=|website=www.stanford.edu|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2007, the [[National Football League]] announced that it intended to trademark the phrase \"The Big Game\" in reference to the [[Super Bowl]],<ref>{{cite news |last=FitzGerald |first=Tom |title=NFL marketers want 'Big Game' trademark; Cal, Stanford fight to protect symbol of football rivalry |url=http://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/NFL-marketers-want-Big-Game-trademark-Cal-2645219.php | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | date=August 23, 2010 |accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref> but soon dropped the plan after being faced with opposition from Cal and Stanford.<ref>{{cite news |last=FitzGerald |first=Tom |title=NFL sidelines its pursuit of Big Game trademark |url=http://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/NFL-drops-effort-to-trademark-Big-Game-phrase-2558977.php | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | date=August 22, 2010 |accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the new [[Levi's Stadium]] in [[Santa Clara, California|Santa Clara]] was proposed as the site of the 2014 Big Game, which according to the traditional rotation should be played at Cal's Memorial Stadium.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abclocal.go.com/kgo/story?section=news/sports/college/football&id=9218115|title=Cal, Stanford consider moving Big Game to Levi's Stadium |date=August 24, 2013|work=KGO-TV|accessdate=25 August 2013}}</ref>  The 2015 game would then be held in Berkeley, reversing the current rotation of odd-numbered years at Stanford and even-numbered years at Cal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/sports/kroichick/article/Cal-ponders-moving-2014-Big-Game-4757839.php|title=Cal ponders moving 2014 Big Game |last=Kroichick|first=Ron|date=August 24, 2013|work=San Francisco Chronicle|accessdate=25 August 2013}}</ref> However, several days later Cal declined the offer.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/sports/ci_23975023/cal-opts-against-big-game-at-levis-stadium|title=Cal opts against Big Game at Levi's Stadium|last=Faraudo|first=Jeff|date=August 29, 2013 |work=San Jose Mercury News|accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Pregame traditions==\n[[File:Lit (332963905).jpg|thumb|2006 Cal Big Game Bonfire Rally]]\nIn the week before the game, both schools celebrate the occasion with rallies, reunions, and luncheons. Cal students hold a traditional pep rally and bonfire at the [[Hearst Greek Theatre]] on the eve of the game, while Stanford students stage the Gaieties, a theatrical production that both celebrates and pokes fun at the rivalry. The week also includes various other athletic events including \"The Big Splash\" ([[water polo]]), \"The Big Spike\" ([[volleyball]]), \"The Big Sweep\" ([[Quidditch]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.californiagoldenblogs.com/2011/4/1/2084349/cal-california-golden-bears-stanford-cardinal-inaugural-division-i-quidditch-teams|title=Cal & Stanford Create Inaugural Division I Quidditch Teams|work=California Golden Blogs|accessdate=20 October 2012}}</ref> \"The Big Freeze\" ([[ice hockey]]), \"The Big Sail\" ([[sailing]]), and the Ink Bowl, a [[Touch football (American)|touch football]] game between the members of the two schools' newspapers. Cal celebrates in San Francisco with an annual cable car rally, hosts a tree chopping rally, has singing competitions, and night rallies through all of the dorms.\n\n===Cal===\n[[File:The Football Players by Douglas Tilden, view 2 - University of California, Berkeley - DSC04938.JPG|thumb|left|150px|''The Football Players'', sculpture by Douglas Tilden, placed in the University of California, Berkeley]]\nThe Big Game Bonfire Rally is a pep and bonfire rally that takes place at University of California, Berkeley in [[Hearst Greek Theatre]] on the eve of Big Game. More than 10,000 students gather to hear the history about [[The Stanford Axe]] and Big Game. The University of California Rally Committee is in charge of the planning and setting up the bonfire, as well as refueling it during the rally. Specifically, freshman members of the UC Rally Committee, as well as freshman band members are sent out with pallets to the chanting of \"freshmen, more wood.\" Several alumni show up to perform traditional rituals. A tradition unique to Cal is the performance of the [[Haka performed by non-New Zealand sports teams|Haka]], a traditional Maori war dance/chant. Traditionally performed by an alumni Yell Leader, the Haka performed was written in the 1960s by a [[California Golden Bears rugby|Cal rugby]] player of Maori descent. The traditional Axe Yell is also made and visits from the [[University of California Men's Octet|UC Men's Octet]] and [[California Golden Overtones|Golden Overtones]] are always expected.  The [[University of California Marching Band]] is also present, playing traditional Cal songs throughout the duration of the Rally. The highlight of the Rally is the lighting of Big Game Bonfire itself, with the fire reaching its zenith at over eight stories.\n\nThe Big Game Bonfire Rally always ends with the reciting of a speech known as the \"[[Andy Smith (American football)|Andy Smith]] Eulogy\" or \"The Spirit of California\". Written by Garff Wilson in remembrance of the fabled Cal football coach, who led the Bears to five straight undefeated seasons starting in 1919 before tragically dying of pneumonia in 1925, the speech closes the Rally annually since 1949.  During the speech, candles are passed out among the attendants and are lit for the singing of the campus alma mater, \"[[All Hail Blue and Gold]].\"<ref name=SFC-120730 /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.cdlib.org/view?docId=hb4v19n9zb;NAAN=13030&doc.view=frames&chunk.id=div00221&toc.id=div00219 |title=Andy Smith Eulogy |author= |date= |publisher=University of California |website=Calisphere |accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the Big Game Bonfire Rally was moved to [[Edwards Stadium]] and the bonfire was cancelled due to a scheduling conflict with a [[Bob Dylan]] concert. Due to TV contracts, the Pac-12 Conference rescheduled the Big Game from its traditional season-ending slot to October 20, and the Greek Theatre was already booked for the Bob Dylan concert. This was the first time the bonfire had not been held since 1892.<ref name=SFC-120730>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/collegesports/article/Cal-Big-Game-bonfire-tradition-doused-3745370.php |title=Cal Big Game bonfire tradition doused |author=Jones, Carolyn |date=30 July 2012 |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref> The bonfire portion of the rally was cancelled again in 2015 due to [[2011\u201317 California drought|the ongoing drought]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.californiagoldenblogs.com/2015/10/25/9613204/no-traditional-bonfire-at-the-2015-big-game-rally-due-to-drought |title=No traditional bonfire at the 2015 Big Game Rally due to drought |author=Yen, Ruey |date=25 October 2015 |website=California Golden Blogs |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=23 October 2017}}</ref><!--The Haka was canceled in 2015?--> In 2016, the Fiat Lux torch was added as a symbol of light, with, \"For the flames of the past, spirit of the present, and light of the future\" engraved on it. In 2018, the big game was rescheduled due to the unhealthy air quality caused by the Bay Area Campfire. All fire/pyrotechnical elements were cut from the rally. The UC Rally Committee immediately began preparations to re-invent the traditional wood burning structure, as they did not want the fire to extinguish like it had almost 30 years earlier at Stanford. In November 2019, a new sheet metal bonfire structure was unveiled.\n\n===Stanford===\nFor decades, Stanford also held a bonfire on the dry lakebed of [[Lake Lagunita]], but this was discontinued in the 1990s due to the lake being a habitat for the [[Vulnerable species|vulnerable]] [[California tiger salamander]].<ref>{{cite press release | title=Bonfire canceled to protect salamander habitat | date=October 7, 1993 | url=http://news-service.stanford.edu/pr/93/931007Arc3114.html | publisher=Stanford University}}</ref> Stanford now holds a Big Game Rally on Angell Field organized by the Stanford Axe Committee. With appearances from the senior football players and various performance groups, it serves to kick off Big Game Week. The story of The Stanford Axe is told by Hal Mickelson, and the Axe Yell is performed by the Yell Leaders of The Stanford Axe Committee. The rally ends with a performance by the [[Stanford Band|Leland Stanford Junior University Marching Band]] and a fireworks show. A student-produced play called \"Gaieties,\" an annual Big Game week tradition since 1911, pokes fun at Cal and serves to pump students up for the Big Game.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stanforddaily.com/2015/11/20/gaieties-chem-31-xxx-is-the-best-class-all-quarter/|title='Gaieties: Chem 31 XXX' is the best class all quarter|last=MacLeod|first=Madeline|date=November 20, 2015|work=The Stanford Daily|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref> Another part of Stanford's tradition was the annual hanging of the substantial \"Beat Cal\" banner upon the four story [[J. Henry Meyer Memorial Library|Meyer Library]] building. This tradition came to an end in 2014 before the building was demolished.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.stanford.edu/news/2014/october/meyer-library-future-10-14-14.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311100135/https://news.stanford.edu/news/2014/october/meyer-library-future-10-14-14.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2017-03-11|title=Stanford's Meyer Library to be replaced with open space|date=2017-03-11|access-date=2017-10-22}}</ref> Since 2015, the banner has been hung on the western facade of [[Cecil H. Green Library|Green Library]].\n\n==Notable games==\n[[File:2010 Big Game.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A group of American football players, surrounded by photographers, lift a plaque upon which is an ax head and an inscription.|Stanford players lift the Stanford Axe after winning the 2010 Big Game]]\n\n===1924===\nBoth teams came into the game unbeaten with a berth in the [[1925 Rose Bowl]] on the line. With its star [[Ernie Nevers]] sidelined due to injuries, Stanford trailed 20\u20136 with under 5 minutes to go, but rallied to score twice to force a 20\u201320 tie and earn the Rose Bowl bid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stanford.scout.com/2/921343.html|title=A Come-Through Story: The 1924 Big Game|date=November 18, 2009|last=Breier|first=John|accessdate=November 16, 2010|publisher=Scout.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716022328/http://stanford.scout.com/2/921343.html|archive-date=July 16, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===1947===\nIn the 50th Big Game, winless Stanford led the 8\u20131 Bears with less than three minutes left in the game, but Cal scored on an 80-yard touchdown pass to clinch a 21\u201318 victory.<ref name=stanbg>{{cite web|url=http://www.gostanford.com/biggame/history.html |title=Big Game History and Tradition |accessdate=November 16, 2010 |publisher=GoStanford.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104111545/http://www.gostanford.com/biggame/history.html |archivedate=January 4, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===1959===\nStanford quarterback [[Dick Norman (football)|Dick Norman]] threw for 401 yards (then an NCAA record, and still a Big Game record), but it was not enough to hold off the Bears, who won 20\u201317.<ref name=stanbg/>\n\n===1972===\nCal drove 62 yards in the final 1:13, culminating in a [[Vince Ferragamo]] touchdown pass to Steve Sweeney for a last-second 24\u201322 Cal victory.<ref name=scout>{{cite web|url=http://california.scout.com/2/814436.html|title=The Big Game: Cal vs. Stanford|date=November 22, 2009|publisher=Scout.com|accessdate=November 16, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525002822/http://www.scout.com/college/california/story/814436-the-big-game-cal-vs-stanford?s=166|archive-date=2017-05-25|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===1974===\nMike Langford nailed a 50-yard field goal on the final play for a 22\u201320 Stanford triumph over the 19th-ranked Bears.<ref name=scout/>\n\n===1982===\n====The Play====\n{{Main|The Play (American football)}}\nThe conclusion of the 85th Big Game on November 20, 1982 would go down as perhaps the most remarkable play in college football history. Cal held a lead late in the game, but Stanford, led by [[John Elway]], drove down the field to retake the lead, and seemingly elevate Elway to the first [[bowl game]] of his college career, since a Stanford victory would have resulted in an invitation to the [[Hall of Fame Bowl]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=15VTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LYcDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1596,5594863|title=Stanford Cards get bowl bid|newspaper=[[The Bulletin (Bend)|The Bulletin]]|date=November 16, 1982|accessdate=February 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn what is now known simply as \"[[The Play (American football)|The Play]],\" four Cal players lateraled the ball five times on a kickoff return with four seconds left on the clock. Kevin Moen, who was also the initial ball carrier, ran for a touchdown while knocking down the final Stanford \"defender,\" trombone player Gary Tyrrell, who had run onto the field with the rest of the band to celebrate prematurely.\n\nThe Play is often recounted with [[KGO-AM|KGO]] radio announcer [[Joe Starkey]]'s emotional call of The Play, which he hailed as \"the most amazing, sensational, dramatic, heartrending, exciting, thrilling finish in the history of college football!\" The legitimacy of The Play has remained controversial among some Stanford fans.  The final score in the official record shows Cal winning by a score of 25\u201320, whereas in many Stanford publications it is recorded as Stanford 20, Cal 19 due to Stanford's contention that a Cal ball carrier had his knee down and the last lateral was actually an illegal forward pass, either of which should have resulted in the end of the play. However, speculation will not erase the final result.\n\nIn 2007, as part of the buildup to The Play's 25th anniversary, the Bay Area News Group asked Verle Sorgen, the Pac-10 Conference's supervisor of instant replay, to review the two disputed laterals according to modern NCAA instant replay review rules. After watching enhanced footage on a modern, large-screen monitor, Sorgen opined that the fifth lateral from Ford to Moen \"was released at the 22 and touched at the 20-1/2. From that, it clearly appears forward.\" Asked for his \"ultimate call,\" Sorgen replied, \"I would be tempted to reverse it...then go out and get the motor running in my car.\"<ref>[https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2007/11/29/upon-further-review-the-play-wouldnt-result-in-cal-win/] Del Grande, Dave. \"Upon further review, The Play wouldn't result in Cal win. Retrieved November 22, 2019.</ref>\n=== 1986 ===\nCal was 1\u20139 in the conference, while Stanford was 7-2 and ranked 16th in the nation. Cal's defense dominated the game - Stanford's quarterback [[John Paye]] was sacked seven times, while Stanford's running game was held to 41 yards. Cal won the game 17\u201311. It was the last game of Cal's coach [[Joe Kapp]], who also coached the Golden Bears in 1982, his first season, when Cal won the Big Game following The Play.<ref>{{Cite book|title=ESPN College Football Encyclopedia|last=McCambridge|first=Michael|publisher=ESPN Books|year=2005|isbn=1-4013-3703-1|location=|pages=188}}</ref>\n\n===1988===\nWith the score tied, Cal marched to the Stanford 3-yard line with 4 seconds remaining in the game. Called \"the Cadillac of kickers in college football\" by Cal coach Bruce Snyder, all Pac-10 and future all-American Robbie Keen lined up for a 21-yard [[Field goal (football)|field goal]] attempt to win the game on the final play. When the ball was snapped, Stanford redshirt freshman Tuan Van Le raced from the left end of the defensive line to block the kick and preserve a 19\u201319 tie. As Stanford was the holder of the Axe going into the game, the tie meant the Axe returned to the Farm for another year. The result was celebrated in the stadium as a victory by Stanford as the Axe was paraded by the Stanford Axe Committee and football players before jubilant Cardinal fans, with stunned Bears fans looking on. This was the only Big Game to end in a tie after 1953 and, under current overtime rules, may be the last Big Game to end tied.<ref name=stanbg/>\n\n===1990===\nThis game had echoes of the 1982 game due to late seesaw scoring, the critical role of fans on the field, and the winning points being scored as time expired.  It has been called \"The Payback\" or \"The Revenge of the Play\" by Stanford fans.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eastbaytimes.com/2010/11/17/1990-when-stanford-staged-its-revenge-of-the-play/|title=1990: When Stanford staged its Revenge of The Play|last=Faraudo|first=Jeff|date=November 17, 2010|work=East Bay Times|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref>  After trailing since the first quarter, left-footed Stanford kicker [[John Hopkins (football)|John Hopkins]] kicked his fourth field goal of the game with 9:56 left to give Stanford its first lead at 18\u201317.  Cal responded with a touchdown and added a [[two-point conversion]] to lead 25\u201318 with 6:03 left.  Stanford stopped Cal on a third and 6 on the Stanford 46 with 2:06 left to play.  After Cal's punt, Stanford took its final possession on its own 13 with 1:54 left.  Escaping two near interceptions and converting a 4th and 6, Stanford moved the ball to the Cal 19 with 0:17 left.  Quarterback [[Jason Palumbis]] threw a touchdown pass to [[Ed McCaffrey]] in the end zone to make it 25\u201324.  With no overtime, and despite the fact that a tie would keep the Axe at Stanford for another year, Cardinal coach Dennis Green quickly went for a two-point conversion. Palumbis' pass into the end zone was intercepted by John Hardy and Cal fans and players engulfed the field, causing a lengthy delay and resulting in a 15-yard delay of game penalty. With 12 seconds left and now kicking from the 50 yard line, Hopkins bounced the ensuing [[onside kick]] off a Cal player and, after being touched by seven players, the ball was recovered by Stanford's Dan Byers on the Cal 37. With 9 seconds left and no time outs, a pass attempt to McCaffrey to set up a field goal fell short, but Palumbis was roughed on the play moving the ball to the 22 yard line. With 5 seconds left, Hopkins connected on a 39-yard field goal into the wind, giving Stanford a 27\u201325 victory as time expired.  This time Stanford students and players engulfed the field.  The late passing and kicking excitement overshadowed two excellent running performances by Cal's [[Russell White]] (177 yards and 2 TD's) and Stanford's [[Glyn Milburn]] (196 yards and 1 TD).  Milburn also led Stanford receiving with 9 receptions for 66 yards and had 117 return yards.  His 379 all-purpose yards set a Pac-10 record at the time and remained Stanford's record until it was eclipsed by [[Christian McCaffrey]]'s 389 all-purpose yards in the 2015 edition of the Big Game.<ref name=bg90>{{cite news|last=Peters|first=Keith| work =Palo Alto Weekly|date=November 19, 1997| title=Big Game Flashback|url=http://www.paloaltoonline.com/weekly/morgue/cover/1997_Nov_19.COVSIDE4.html| accessdate =November 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2000===\nStanford's [[Casey Moore]] caught the winning touchdown on the final play of the first-ever Big Game to go into [[Overtime (sports)|overtime]].<ref name=stanbg/>\n\n===2009===\nCal's Michael Mohamed intercepted an [[Andrew Luck]] pass at the Cal 3-yard line with 1:36 left to preserve a Cal win over #14 Stanford, 34\u201328. It was also a rare Big Game where both teams were nationally ranked.<ref name=abc>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory?id=9147052&tqkw=&tqshow=|title=Cal beats #14 Stanford 34\u201328 in Big Game|publisher=abcnews.com|date=November 21, 2009|accessdate=November 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2010===\nSixth-ranked Stanford, in a 48\u201314 victory, ties Cal's 1975 record for most points scored in a Big Game.<ref name=Cal2010>{{cite news|url=http://www.calbears.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/112010aaa.html |title=Cal Football Postgame Notes \u2013 113th Big Game vs. Stanford (Sat., Nov. 20) |publisher=CBS Interactive |date=November 20, 2010 |accessdate=November 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404073419/http://www.calbears.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/112010aaa.html |archivedate=April 4, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===2013===\nWinning 63\u201313, #10 Stanford set the record for most points scored in a Big Game, shattering the previous record of 48 shared by Cal in 1975 and Stanford in 2010.  The 50-point victory margin also set a Big Game record, breaking the previous record that had stood for 83 years when Stanford beat Cal 41\u20130 in 1930. The 76 total points scored by both teams broke the record of 66 set in 2000.  With the victory, Stanford clinched the Pac-12 North Division Championship while Cal ended its season at 1\u201311, the most losses in one season in Cal football history.<ref name=2013SFChron>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/Stanford-cruises-by-Cal-in-Big-Game-ties-Oregon-5006535.php|title=Stanford routs Cal, reaches Pac-12 title game|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|last=FitzGerald|first=Tom|date=November 23, 2013|accessdate=November 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 ===\nThe 2018 Big Game was originally scheduled to be played on November 17, but was rescheduled to December 1 at 12:00 noon, because of unhealthy air quality in the Bay Area caused by the [[Camp Fire (2018)|Camp Fire]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/california-wildfires-force-cal-stanford-to-reschedule-the-big-game-to-dec-1/|title=California wildfires force Cal, Stanford to reschedule 'The Big Game' to Dec. 1|work=CBSSports.com|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en}}</ref>  Stanford continued its streak, winning for the ninth time in a row, beating Cal 23\u201313.\n\n=== 2019 ===\nDown 20\u201317 with 2:23 remaining, the Cal offense engineered a six-play, 75-yard drive culminating in a 16-yard touchdown run from quarterback Chase Garbers to give the Bears their first lead of the game. Cal linebacker Evan Weaver would seal the 24\u201320 victory for the Bears with a dramatic fourth-and-one stop on Cardinal running back Cameron Scarlett on the subsequent possession, setting off a raucous celebration on Stanford's home turf as the Axe would return to Berkeley after nearly a decade away. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=401114182|title=Garbers' late touchdown lifts Cal past Stanford 24-20|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2020-03-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Game results==\n\n{{Sports rivalry series table\n| format = compact | cols = 2 | series_summary = yes\n| legend_tie_text = Ties\n| team1 = California \n| team1style = {{NCAA color cell|California Golden Bears}}\n| team2 = Stanford\n| team2style = {{NCAA color cell|Stanford Cardinal}}\n| 1892 | San Francisco | Stanford | 14 | California | 10\n| 1892 | San Francisco | California | 10 | Stanford | 10\n| 1893 | San Francisco | California | 6 | Stanford | 6\n| 1894 | San Francisco | Stanford | 6 | California | 0\n| 1895 | San Francisco | California | 6 | Stanford | 6\n| 1896 | San Francisco | Stanford | 20 | California | 0\n| 1897 | San Francisco | Stanford | 28 | California | 0\n| 1898 | San Francisco | California | 22 | Stanford | 0\n| 1899 | San Francisco | California | 30 | Stanford | 0\n| 1900 | San Francisco | Stanford | 5 | California | 0\n| 1901 | San Francisco | California | 2 | Stanford | 0\n| 1902 | San Francisco | California | 16 | Stanford | 0\n| 1903 | San Francisco | California | 6 | Stanford | 6\n| 1904 | Berkeley | Stanford | 18 | California | 0\n| 1905 | Stanford | Stanford | 12 | California | 5\n| 1919 | Stanford | California | 14 | Stanford | 10\n| 1920 | Berkeley | California | 38 | Stanford | 0\n| 1921 | Stanford | California | 42 | Stanford | 7\n| 1922 | Stanford | California | 28 | Stanford | 0\n| 1923 | Berkeley | California | 9 | Stanford | 0\n| 1924 | Berkeley | California | 20 | Stanford | 20\n| 1925 | Stanford | Stanford |